<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0001 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-02 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Strives to Establish Unified Customs Tariffs System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) Secretariat is currently working on formulating a unified
customs tariffs scheme toward non-GCC members, the Kuwait News
Agency (KUNA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The GCC Assistant Secretary General for Economic Affairs, Abdul
Latif Al-Meqrin, told KUNA today that the secretariat had been
looking for a new formula to replace the current goods'
classification method.
</P>
<P>
Meqrin said the secretariat was keen on formulating the new
scheme to be presented to the upcoming meeting of the GCC finance
and economic committee due to be held in early June.
</P>
<P>
Meqrin, who was speaking after a meeting of the trade and
commerce chambers in the GCC, said the secretariat was committed
to the outcome of the GCC Muscat Summit, which was held in Oman in
December 1995, during which the leaders demanded that the customs
tariffs scheme be drafted by mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the GCC's unified tariffs is the main part
of an economic pact aimed at creating a common market, which could
give birth to one of the biggest consumer blocks in the world,
with imports of more than 50 billion U.S. dollars and a gross
domestic product (GDP) of some 200 billion dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
A GCC technical committee completed categorizing 970 out of
1,278 goods according to the three main international categories.
</P>
<P>
Meqrin said if the committee failed to reach the desired
formula, it would stop its meetings. But if the formula was
agreed upon by the GCC finance ministers, it would be referred to
the forthcoming GCC summit.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general of the Saudi Chambers of Trade and
Commerce, Abdullah Al-Dabagh, said it was very important to
establish a unified customs tariffs scheme in the GCC to confront
the world economic challenges.
</P>
<P>
Dabagh said if the scheme was not attained, "the GCC States
will not be effective enough in their meetings with international
economic powers."
</P>
<P>
The GCC "cannot establish its economic regional bloc unless it
establishs the custom union. Our trade partners will not
seriously deal with us if the bloc is not founded," added Dabagh.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Meqrin said the GCC Secretariat had briefed the
heads of the commerce chambers on the power link-up among the GCC
member states, which had already been endorsed by the GCC leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Muscat summit had endorsed the power connection project and
called on the private sector to finance it. Its primary cost was 2
billion dollars and is expected to save 24 billion dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the GCC finance and electricity undersecretaries
had assigned the Gulf Organization for Industrial Consultancy to
study the feasibility of the project.
</P>
<P>
Meqrin said the Bahraini Chamber of Commerce had proposed the
establishment of a Gulf Bank to finance Gulf projects, but the
participants showed disagreement. They argued that there were
other Gulf financial institutions that could do the job instead.
</P>
<P>
However, a committee comprising the secretaries general of the
GCC trade and commerce chambers was formed to discuss the
possibility of holding a meeting among factories' owners in the
Gulf and their European counterparts, Meqrin said.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Bahrain, Qatar and
the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
