<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children's Education Deteriorated in Tanzania: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is experiencing a
deteriorating period for children's education, a senior official in
the Ministry of Community Development,Women and Children Affairs
has noted.
</P>
<P>
In a paper on the children and women situation in Tanzania
prepared for the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) high
level review meeting, which was held here today, Ms. Priscilla
Ole Kambaine, Director of Women and Children Affair in the
minstry said that the situation was illustrated by declining
school enrolment rates, increasing number of school dropouts and
poor perfomance rates, particularly for girls.
</P>
<P>
She said, school aged children enrolled in primary school
declined from 96 percent in 1980 to 74 percent in 1994 and that
the proportion of children enrolled in a grade corresponding with
their age declined from 70 to 53 per- cent.
</P>
<P>
The director said that the fact has put Tanzania at a level
almost equivalent to other sub-Saharan countries and far from the
goal of universal primary education.
</P>
<P>
She said that dropouts rates increased from 17 percent in 1976
to 34 percent in 1986. The main reason for school dropouts is
poverty or inadequate means to meet the costs of schooling, she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
