<HEADLINE> Link Between BSE and CJD Not Confirmed by  WHO Expert Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Doubts remain about a link between
mad cow disease and a new fatal human brain disorder as an
international expert meeting here ended Wednesday with a vague
conclusion and advices to minimize any human risk arising from
eating beef.
</P>
<P>
"A link has not yet been proven between the newly-recognized
variant of Creutzfeldt-Jacob Disease (V-CJD) in the United Kingdom
and the effective exposure to the BSE agent", concluded the April
2-3 symposium organized by the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
But circumstantial evidence suggests exposure to BSE (Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathies, namely mad cow disease) may be the
most likely explanation, it was added.
</P>
<P>
To verify the link needs further studies, on both V-CJD and
BSE, according to WHO at a press conference Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
BSE, or Transmissible Spongiform Encephalopathies (TSE)
occurring in cattle, was first identified in 1986 in UK and has
since caused over 160,000 cases there and over 100 others
elsewhere in Europe. The BSE agent is allegedly attributed to 10
cases in UK of its human equivalent, V-CJD, including eight
deaths.
</P>
<P>
The suspected link was officially announced by London on March
20 and has since provoked public panic and a ban on British beef
importation by many countries around the world.
</P>
<P>
It was reiterated at Wednesday's news conference that the 10
V-CJD cases, if any link with BSE true, were most likely
contracted before 1989 when the British government launched
sanitary measures to check the cow epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The steps taken regarding cattle feed and the removal of bovine
offal from market along with other precautionary measures at farm,
slaughter and meat processing levels, are deemed by WHO as
effective, if strictly implemented, in containing BSE and
consequently reducing any human risk of contracting V-CJD from
eating beef.
</P>
<P>
Among the recommendations to minimize any human risk, WHO
suggested no part of animal showing signs of TSE -- which occur in
several animal species, nor tissues likely to contain TSE agent
should enter any food chain, human or animal.
</P>
<P>
Affecting animals' nervous system, TSE agent is often found in
such related tissues as brains and spinal cord and also in lymphs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, said WHO, all countries should ensure the killing and
safe disposal of TSE-affected animals and ban the use of ruminant
tissues in ruminant feed.
</P>
<P>
WHO also urged efforts towards rapid TSE diagnosis. According to
experts at the news conference, testing technology need to be improved
so as to identify TSE infections as early as possible. It often takes
four to five years for an animal to develop TSE after being infected.
</P>
<P>
Experts believed any human risk could be reduced to minimal with
the measures they recommended being strictly carried out. However,
they said, complete safety is not possible.
</P>
<P>
Veterinary and medical experts attending the WHO meeting considered
milk and milk products are safe as milk does not transmit BSE agent.
So are gelatin and tallow produced under effective rendering
procedures, which, they said, can inactivate the BSE infectivity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
