<HEADLINE> Conference on Africa's Oil Trading to Convene in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The UN Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD) said today that it is organizing a large
conference in Harare of Zimbabwe in an effort to help improve oil
trading, risk management and financing practices in sub-Saharan
Africa's oil sector.
</P>
<P>
The conference, organized by the UNCTAD in cooperation with the
Eastern and Southern African Trade and Development Bank, will take
place in Harare on April 15-17.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNCTAD, studies have shown that African
countries can make major savings through improving oil trading,
risk management and financing practices. Oil importers alone could
save over 500 million U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
By bring together key decision makers from sub-Saharan's oil
and finance sectors, the conference is hoped to create the
momentum needed to implement important changes, the UNCTAD said.
</P>
<P>
Senior executives of a large number of African oil companies,
refineries, end users and African banks, as well as experts from
western banks and oil exchanges are expected to attend the event.
</P>
</TEXT>
