<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lebanese Government Reiterates Ban on Street Demonstrations (by Shao Jie) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Responding to a decision of labor
unions to stage a protest sit-in coincidently with French
President Jacques Chirac's visit to Lebanon, the Lebanese
government tonight reiterated a ban on street demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Lebanese government also announced that it was
determined to continue the dialogue with the General Workers
Confederation (GWC).
</P>
<P>
The powerful GWC, which groups various trade unions with an
estimated membership of 400,000, took the decision last week to
stage the protest sit-in in front of the parliament building on
April 4, to coincide a scheduled address to be made by Chirac in
the 128-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
In a notification handed to the Interior Ministry, the GWC
said that it would carry out the action "in protest against the
government's failure to meet demands of the workers and the
people."
</P>
<P>
In another notification to House Speaker Nabih Berri, the
confederation said that it "sees in the Council of Deputies (the
parliament) the competent authority capable to correct the track
of the government and its intention to ignore the righteous
demands."
</P>
<P>
The GWC is demanding a 76 percent rise in wages in private and
public sectors and a doubling of the minimum wage level to
500,000 Lebanese pounds (313 U.S. dollars) from the present 250,000
Lebanese pounds.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the government to scrap the three-year-old
demonstration ban and suspend the implementation of a
controversial law on organizing the country's private broadcast
media industry.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a regular session of the Council of Ministers,
government spokesman and Information Minister Farid Mkari
stressed that that the demand raised by the labors for a wage
increase should be resolved by a dialogue with the employers in
which the government could play a role of "arbitrator."
</P>
<P>
He blamed the GWC for a stop of the dialogue and the
decision to stage the sit-in on the occasion when Lebanon is
receiving its state guest.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on the measures the government would take
to confront the sit-in, the information minister reiterated the
government's "well-known and clear" decision of banning street
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that his government would continue the dialogue
with the GWC until a solution is achieved satisfying all the
sides. "But if the GWC insists on the sit-in, the government is
against this sit-in especially at a time when the country is
receiving its state guest."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Lebanese Defense Minister Mohsen Dalloul
stressed today that the army would work to guarantee a successful
visit of French President Chirac to Lebanon and would "not allow
anyone to ruin the safe circumstance of this visit."
</P>
<P>
He said Lebanon is making efforts to eliminate the Israeli
occupation and Chirac's visit would help reach this goal.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Berri said earlier that the sit-in planned by the
GWC "is tantamount to collaboration with Israel to undermine
Chirac's visit and this is completely unacceptable during this
historic visit."
</P>
<P>
He said he would order security forces to stop the labor
protest Thursday in front of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the GWC is facing an increasing pressure
to put off the sit-in or change the venue in order to avert an
embarrassment during Chirac's visit, the first by a serving French
president since Lebanon gained independence from the French
mandate in 1943.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's three top leaders, President Elias Hrawi, House
Speaker Berri and Prime Minister Rafik Al Hariri held this morning
their third meeting in one week to weight a united stand on the
labors' move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
