<HEADLINE> Georgian President Stresses Turkey's Role in Restoring Peace in Caucasus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze said today that it would be impossible to restore
peace and stability in the Caucasus without Turkey's contributions.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze, who arrived here at noon for a two-day state
visit to Turkey, made the remark at a banquet Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel gave in his honor at the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian president expressed his satisfaction that the
bilateral ties between Georgia and Turkey are increasingly
turning into a state of "continuous dialogue."
</P>
<P>
He said he had unfolded an initiative entitled "Peaceful
Caucasus," which aims at bringing peace and stability to this
turbulent part of the world, adding that this would be one of the
topics to be discussed during his talks with Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said that Shevardnadze's visit to Turkey would
contribute further to the existing good ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president praised Shevardnadze as a "great
statesman who has a great knowledge of world and regional
affairs," adding that "The close cooperation of Turkey and Georgia
on regional issues is closely tied up with the close interests of
the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Demirel said that apart from political issues, he will hold
talks on economic cooperation with his Georgian counterpart
Shevardnadze, saying that a host of agreements would be signed
during the visit.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Nurettin Nurkan said
Monday that Demirel and Shevardnadze would also discuss the
Soupsa-Ceyhan oil pipeline project.
</P>
<P>
The projected pipeline from the Georgian port of Soupsa to the
Turkish Mediterranean port of Ceyhan is an alternative route for
transporting oil produced in the Caspian region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
