<HEADLINE> Finance Policy Will Not Change, Says S. African President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua)-- South Africa's finance policy
would remain unchanged as incoming Finance Minister Trevor Manuel
steped into the shoes of his predecessor Chris Liebenberg on
Thursday, President Nelson Mandela said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at his official Cape Town residence,
Mandela said Manuel would follow exactly the same policies
initiated by his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the sharp fall in the local currency rand on the
financial market, Mandela said the currency had been low for some
time.
</P>
<P>
Manuel, former Trade and Industry Minister, was appointed to
take over Liebenberg's post in a cabinet reshuffle announced by
Mandela on March 28.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, outgoing Finance Minister Liebenberg said he was
not worried about the rand's weakening against major foreign
currencies, saying the fundamentals were still in place.
</P>
<P>
Liebenberg said South Africa was not going to throw away its
foreign reserves defending the rand.
</P>
<P>
The fluctuations in the value of the currency were to be
expected, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, dealers said the rand was off its earlier all-time
lows against the dollar by midday on Wednesday, but remained weak
in an extremely volatile market.
</P>
<P>
The local unit hit an all-time low of 4.11 to the dollar in
intra-day trade, before recovering to 4.09 at midday. It closed
at 4.0075 on Tuesday. The previous record low was 4.03, reached
on February 21 amid rumours Mandela was ill. enditem

