<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Tries to Ease Beef Crisis Scare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- British Agriculture Minister
Douglas Hogg told the parliament this afternoon that the
government was taking measures to ensure that slaughterhouses
would begin processing beef again, which has been interrupted by
the wave of the mad cow disease scare for past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who is being attacked by both the European Union
and British farmers for failing to act quickly and decisively
enough to eliminate BSE, known as the mad cow disease, said that
public confidence in British beef is beginning to return.
</P>
<P>
He told the House of Commons that government officials are
working on a quality assurance scheme based on identifying
BSE-free Herds.
</P>
<P>
Hogg accused the EU of offering an "unhelpful"response to the
beef crisis and refusing to lift its worldwide ban on British beef
exports.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the British government is still holding a
difficult bargaining with the EU on how to overcome the beef
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The British government is reported to have won the EU backing
to destroy more than four million older cattle in the next six
years and remove them from the food chain.
</P>
<P>
But the EU criticized Britain for refusing to provide detailed
figures on the incidence of BSE in the UK to other EU member
states.
</P>
<P>
The EU is considering paying 70 percent of the cost of
Britain's slaughter program, instead of the 80 percent demanded by
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Mean while, Germany and Belgium are opposed to the proposal that
the EU would buy up meat from British bulls and steers at
competitive prices to prop up the market.
</P>
<P>
Germany also insisted that the only solution that would satisfy
the Bonn government would be for Britain to slaughter all herds
with any record of BSE infection.
</P>
<P>
Britain now is given until April 30 to produce comprehensive
plans for the selective culling of herds positively identified
with BSE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
