<HEADLINE> U.S. Commerce Secretary's Plane Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. military plane carrying
U.S. Commerce Secretary Ron Brown crashed on a flight from the
northern Bosnian city of Tuzla to Croatia today, U.S. Attorney
General Jenet Reno said here.
</P>
<P>
"We have news that Commerce Secretary Ron Brown's plane is down
in Bosnia. The wreckage has been sighted. They are investigating,"
Reno told reporters.
</P>
<P>
She announced that U.S. President Bill Clinton had cancelled a
speech at the Justice Department this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
White House and State Department spokesmen have said that
Brown's plane was three hours overdue on a flight from Tuzla to
Dubrovnik on the Adriatic coast of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that the
wreckage had been sighted "in the water" but is was still
uncertain that it was Brown's plane.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old U.S. Commerce Secretary was leading a
delegation of leading American businessmen looking for
opportunities in the post-war reconstruction of the Balkan
nations.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon and State Department officials said that they didn't
know whether dozens of U.S. corporation executives were aboarding
Brown's plane. 
</P>
