<HEADLINE> French Defense Minister Ends Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 3 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister
Charles Millon left Riyadh this afternoon, winding up a two-day
visit to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference this morning, the French minister
said he has had lengthy talks with Saudi Defense Minister Prince
Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz on matters of mutual concern to the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Millon added that during the talks he had expressed "France's
conviction that Saudi Arabia was maintaining regional balance of
power as well as security."
</P>
<P>
He said that "France is pleased with the efforts done within
the framework of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) and with
the GCC role in maintaining balance of power and security in the
region."
</P>
<P>
According to the Saudi Press Agency, their talks also covered
ways of combating terrorism, the outcome of the Sharm el-Sheikh
summit conference during which Saudi Arabia and France held
identical views, the situation in Iraq, and matters related to
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Millon said he had expressed his country's hope that Iran would
regain its position in the international community. But, he said,
this would require that "Iran be committed to a clear-cut policy,
averting any practices that distort public order in the region and
avoiding such behaviors as giving rise to the present criticism
and creating tension in the region."
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the sealing off of Palestinian territories
by Israel, the French minister spelled out "the necessity of
maintaining the peace process through negotiations," adding that
his government will "spare no effort to see the negotiations
resumed under the best possible conditions."
</P>
<P>
The French defense minister arrived in Riyadh Tuesday on his
second visit to Saudi Arabia in less than six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
