<HEADLINE> Oil Revenues of OPEC Member States Increase in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The revenues of the OPEC member
states from oil sales reached 141.1 billion U.S. dollars in 1995,
recording an increase of 13 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued by the Egyptian General Petroleum
Corporation (EGPC), the oil revenues of the members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) were 124.9
billion dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The increase in revenues was due to a rise in oil prices and
exports, the state-run Middle East News Agency (MENA) quoted the
report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is the only OPEC member whose oil revenues dropped last
year, the report said. Its oil revenues decreased by 8.1 percent
from those in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that all OPEC members, with the exception
of Iraq and Libya, increased their oil exports in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia earned an estimated 48 billion dollars from oil
sales last year as compared with 43.4 billion dollars in the
previous year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
OPEC expects oil prices to drop if Iraq accepts a U.N. offer
which will allow it to sell a certain amount of oil to purchase
badly-needed food and medicines, MENA said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has called on both OPEC and non-OPEC oil producers to
shoulder their responsibility to deal with a possible return of
Iraq to the world oil market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
