<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Minister Attacks Terrorist Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 3 (Xinhua)-- Zambian Legal Affairs Minister Remm
Mushota today described death threats to ministers from a secret
group called Black Mamba (poisonous snake) as a move by
desperate people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Zambia television, Mushota said Zambians should look
for democratic ways of gaining political power rather than by threats
because the latter would spoil the good image the country had enjoyed
ever since.
</P>
<P>
Mushota noted that such threats would give a set back to the
government's efforts to attract investment both from local and
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
He revealed the government had some information that opposition
United National Independence Party (UNIP) and Zambia Democratic
Congress (ZDC) were behind the secret group.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the government did not want to intervene with the
professional investigations of the police.
</P>
<P>
But earlier, the two opposition parties outrightly denied their
linkage to Black Mamba.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister reiterated that the government would still
go ahead to recommend the adoption of the draft constitution by
parliament because there was no legal provision in Zambia for a
constituent assembly.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that about 10 ministers and deputy ministers as
well as speaker of the national assembly have received the death
threats sent by Black Mamba through anonymous letters.
</P>
<P>
The group threatened to eliminate ministers and the speaker if
they insisted on adoption of the draft constitution by
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Some opposition parties and other organizations have demanded the
government to adopt the new constitution through a constituent
assembly and a national referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
