<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK to Impose Tougher Sentences on Persistent Offenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The British government unveiled
this afternoon new plans to introduce tougher sentences for
persistent offenders.
</P>
<P>
In order to crack down on the mounting crime, British Home
Secretary Michael Howard told the parliament that those repeatedly
committing sexual and violent offences would get life terms, while
early release would be abolished automatically.
</P>
<P>
People convicted of dealing in hard drugs on more than three
occasions would get a minimum term of seven years, he said.
</P>
<P>
And persistent burglars would be jailed for a minimum of three
years, along with seizing their assets.
</P>
<P>
He told the parliament that he wanted to ensure that criminals
were properly punished and he promised +honesty in sentencing+.
</P>
<P>
That means, he explained, that in future there will be no
automatic early release and prisoners will have to earn remission
by their good behavior.
</P>
<P>
The home secretary, who launched a white paper detailing the
above said plans, said that it is expected that the prison
population will rise by 10,000.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the changes in sentencing will have to be phased in,
to allow a dozen new prisons to be built.
</P>
<P>
Howard said that he plans to introduce a bill on this issue in
the next session of parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
