<HEADLINE> Trial Of Former Government Officials To Resume Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The trial of senior officials
of Ethiopia's former Mengistu regime will resume here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Central High Court were quoted by the
Ethiopian News Agency today as saying that the court will listen
to prosecution evidences on the genocide and crime against
humanity they were accused.
</P>
<P>
The trial of former government officials and military officers
started on December 13, 1994. Of the 66 former government
officials and military officers, including former president
Mengistu Haile-Mariam and former acting president Tesfaye
Gebre-Kidan, 45 were brought into dock.
</P>
<P>
Those who were on trial in absentia include Mengistu and
Tesfaye. Mengistu is living in exile in Zimbabwe while Tesfaye is
now hiding in the Italian embassy here for asylum.
</P>
<P>
The charges filed by the special prosecutor range from
genocide to abuse of power committed by the officials
individually or collectively as members of the then ruling
Military Council.
</P>
<P>
According to an over 200-page dossier distributed to the
defendants and their defense lawyers on November 28, 1995, the
charges leveled against the defendants included among others the
detention of 2,394 civilians and the confiscation of property
worth about 11 million Birr (less than 2 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The court was adjourned from February 13, 1996 at the request
of the special prosecutor who wanted to have enough time to
collect full evidences and due to the absence from court by two
of the defendants because of illnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
