<HEADLINE> UK Government Promises Referendum on Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The British government has promised
here today to hold a national referendum on the crucial single
currency issue if the Parliament decides to take Britain into the
European Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind told a press conference today
"We have decided to make a commitment in our election manifesto
that if the government decided to join a single currency during
the course of the next parliament, that decision would be subject
to confirmation in a referendum."
</P>
<P>
Rifkind said that the government believed a referendum would be
necessary as the currency issue would not be resolved at a general
election.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet would first decide on whether to join, with the
decision passed to Parliament if ministers decided to go in, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the all-party European Movement said that it would
spearhead the fight for a "yes" vote. Former minister Edwina
Currie said she was very pleased that the government "however
grudgingly," was moving towards a single currency.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Prime Minister John Major hopes the the
referendum pledge will heal deep splits in the Conservative party
over its European policy, enabling it to concentrate on preparing
for the election to be held in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
The European Union hopes to launch a single European currency
in 1999, but many Conservatives consider joining the single
currency as a dangerous move towards a federal Europe with power
concentrated in Brussels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
