<HEADLINE> Mudenge On Domestic, Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Resolving the twin issues of land
ownership and black economic empowerment will be the priority of
the government after the recent presidential election, Foreign
Minister Stan Mudenge said today.
</P>
<P>
He told foreign diplomats here that resolving the issues of
black land hunger and black empowerment in business, as
highlighted in President Robert Mugabe's election campaign, were
not an electioneering gimmick but would now be the government's
major preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
As for black economic empowerment, better known as
indigenization, Mudenge said the government wanted to create
opportunities for black people to find a meaningful role in the
economic life of their country, which was denied them in the
past.
</P>
<P>
"I need to make it known, in case there are misunderstandings
that as far as both questions are concerned, the government does
not seek revenge, victimization, or any form of racist treatment
against the white members of our community. We have no intention
of robbing Tom to give Jack," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"There is, therefore, a great need to look after their
particular needs to create a more equitable distribution of
wealth in the country," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, ruled by British settlers for almost 90 years until
independence in 1980, still has a skewed land ownership pattern
with most of the country's agricultural land owned by some 4,500
white farmers.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe would always try to improve on the
achievements to date in the area of good governance, the rule of
law, protection of human rights and the quest for justice.
</P>
<P>
On the international scene, Mudenge said, the end of the cold
war had improved the world situation and created conditions for
slowing down the arms race.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Zimbabwe will next week sign the convention
making Africa a nuclear free zone, he said, adding that Zimbabwe
is also in the process of ratifying the chemical weapons
convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Monetary Union under Threat, Says Bank Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The launch of a single European
currency in 1999 is under threat because of the recent slowdown in
Europe's economies, the Governor of the Bank of England Eddie
George conceded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting in Frankfurt of the European Monetary
Institute (EMI), the forerunner of the planned European Central
Bank, George highlighted the poor record of member states on
curbing public deficits, one of the key convergence targets of the
Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
This has been caused by higher than planned levels of public
spending as governments in several European Union economies have
been caught in the trap between lower tax revenues and burgeoning
social security payments, he said.
</P>
<P>
The EMI's annual report, published Tuesday, accepts that in the
large majority of the 15 EU member states, public deficits were
well in excess of the levels needed to meet the criteria for a
single currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
