<HEADLINE> Taliban Ready to Talk With Afghan Govt -- Mestiri </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban Militia, who
have been vowing to topple the Afghan government led by President
Burhanuddin Rabbani, today offered to negotiate with Rabbani's
regime, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
UN special envoy to Afghanistan Mehmud Mestiri, who was on a
one-day visit to Kabul, was quoted as saying, "The number two of
the Taliban, Mohammed Rabbani, told us his movement was ready to
negotiate".
</P>
<P>
"They say they are ready to talk tomorrow, and these words are
in the mouth of the Taliban for the very first time," he added.
</P>
<P>
"If the Taliban are ready to talk and President Rabbani is
ready to talk, this is already something," he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers said if the Taliban's offer for talks is serious, it
will be a significant change in its policy.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Taliban had refused to hold negotiations with the
Rabbani's government and repeatedly said it would not consider
sharing power with any other factions.  
</P>
