<HEADLINE> UN Peace Mission to Move into Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The UN peace mission to
Afghanistan would move to the eastern Afghan city of Jalalabad
next week, reports coming from Kabul said today.
</P>
<P>
UN special envoy to Afghanistan Mehmud Mestiri, who was on a
one-day visit to Kabul, was quoted as saying that his mission
would move to Jalalabad from its present office in Islamabad next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that it would be the first time for the UN to
set up a base in the war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We will be moving to Jalalabad next week in order to be closer
to Kabul and the other major Afghan centers," Mestiri said.  "The
decision to move was taken by the UN secretary general following
my reports to him."
</P>
<P>
He said the move would give his mission easier access to Kabul
and the provincial strongholds including Kandahar, Herat,
Mazar-i-Sharif and Bamyan.
</P>
<P>
Jalalabad, which is 180 kilometers east of Kabul, lies on the
main road linking the besieged Afghan capital with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Mestiri said his mission had planned to move to Kabul, but UN
officials vetoed the plan for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Kabul has been under regular rocket attacks allegedly launched
by the Taliban Militia since last October when Taliban advanced to
only five kilometers away from the city.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the move was significant for the UN peace efforts
in Afghanistan. The UN has been repeatedly criticized for failing
to maintain a permanent presence in the country.
</P>
<P>
The move could also affect other UN agencies which maintain
only sub-offices in Afghanistan, the analysts added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
