<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Defends Raising of Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A minister today said the widely
criticized fuel price hike on Monday was a collective decision
made by the government and local oil companies following an 11
percent decline of the local currency against the U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Economists criticized the increase as a move that will have a
negative impact on the economy, increase commodity prices, fuel
inflation and erode disposable imcomes.
</P>
<P>
Transport and Energy Minister Simon Moyo said this scenario
had portrayed the government as "irresponsible," a perception was
far from the truth.
</P>
<P>
Defending the increase, Moyo said it was not the
responsibility of his ministry alone to raise or increase fuel
prices as portrayed by "some uninformed or misinformed
individuals or organizations".
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that the increase was the result of the 11
percent decline of the Zimbabwe Dollar since July last year
thereby increasing costs which have to be paid in foreign
currency, did not make the government irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, petrol went up by three percent, diesel by nine
percent and aviation fuels by between 17 and 20 percent. 
</P>
