<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Factory Orders in U.S. Down Sharply in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Factory orders in U.S. plunged
by 1.4 percent in February, the largest decrease in 10 months, the
U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The drop was due mostly to a huge decline in the volatile
transportation sector. Orders excluding transportation were up
slightly by 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department said orders for both durable and
non-durable goods totaled a seasonally adjusted 304.4 billion
dollars in February, down from 308.8 billion in January.
</P>
<P>
It was the second decline in three months and the steepest
since orders fell 2.2 percent last April.
</P>
<P>
Orders are considered a key gauge of the nation's manufacturing
strength and an increase could lead to greater production and more
jobs.
</P>
<P>
In February, the transportation orders plunged by 11.7 percent
after a 3 percent fall in January. Orders for durable goods fell
by 2.3 percent and orders for nondurable goods were down by 0.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing economy has been weak for months. It rose by
6.7 percent last year comparing to a 10.3 percent gain in 1994.
The weakness is just part of the sluggishness that had affected
much of the overall economy which grew only 0.5 percent at an
annual rate in the final quarter of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders inched up 0.1 percent, the sixth
straight increase. A growing backlog suggests more jobs and longer
production lines may be needed to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
Inventories, another sign of future activity, edged up 0.2
percent after a 0.7 percent advance in January. That resulted in a
1.39 inventories-to-shipments ratio, down from 1.40 a month
earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Daily: Serbs to Become Minority in Serbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A drastic drop in the birth rate
is threatening to reduce Serbs in Serbia to a minority group, the
Belgrade daily Vecernje Novosti said today.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted Professor Marko Mladenovic as saying that Serb
population would be sharply reduced soon unless the Serbs realized
that bearing children and unselfishly raising families was their
most important task.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1991 census, Serbia, which formed the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia with Montenegro in 1991, had a population
of 9,778,991, of whom 6,446,595 were Serbs, 139,299 Montenegrin,
323,625 Yugoslavs, 1,674,353 ethnic Albanians, 342,942 ethnic
Hungarians, 246,411 Muslims, 140,237 Gypsies, 105,406 ethnic
Croats, and 26,876 ethnic Bulgarians.
</P>
<P>
According to demographic estimates, the population in central
Serbia will be reduced by a third in a few decades, while ethnic
Albanians populating Serbia's southern Kosovo province will
double, said Mladenovic.
</P>
<P>
The average annual birth rate is 2.02 percent in Kosovo and
Metohija, 0.8 percent in central Serbia and 0.18 percent in the
northern Vojvodina province.
</P>
<P>
In central Serbia, however, the number of births and deaths is
approximately the same, while in Vojvodina the mortality is even
higher than birth rate. But in Kosovo the birth rate exceeds the
death rate seven times.
</P>
<P>
Conducive to the drop of population in Serbia is the departure
of young Serbs from Yugoslavia, Mladenovic said, adding that half
a million youths had left the country in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Mladenovic warned that if this trend continues, the birth rate
in Serbia would drop to half of the death rate, thus plunging the
Serbs into minorities in Serbia in the future with only old people
remaining in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Campaign Intensified in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The National Narcotics Control
Commission today convened a plenary session, at which it urged
local governments to intensify the fight against drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that by the end of 1995, 520,000 people
in China were registered as drug abusers.
</P>
<P>
Since the National People's Congress's Decision on Eradicating
Illegal Dealing in Narcotics was promulgated in 1990, all local
governments have adopted effective measures in the anti-drug
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1995, China's police dealt with 57,524
cases, arrested 73,734 offenders, and confiscated 2,376 kilograms
of heroin, 1,110 kilograms of opium, and 466 kilograms of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
The same year, customs handled 30 cases, and confiscated 52
kilograms of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Last year China arrested 12,990 persons involved in drugs,
9,801 of whom were convicted, with 2,032 having been sentenced to
death or life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China had opened 565 drug
rehabilitation centers, treating some 80,000 drug abusers every
year.
</P>
<P>
The commission acknowledged that the current situation is
stark, noting that the number of drug abusers in the country is on
the rise.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, a national conference will be held
this year to work out plans on the anti-drug campaign for the next
five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Ponders Over Signing SADC Water Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia today declined to state
when it will sign the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) protocol on shared water resources, saying it needs more
time to study the document.
</P>
<P>
Energy and Water Development Minister Edith Nawakwi told
reporters here that Zambia is approaching the issues cautiously
due to the critical importance of the Zambezi River waters to
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
She explained that sharing of the Zambezi River water in such
ways as individual countries tapping from it would have more
consequences on Zambia than any other state in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Zambezi, the largest river in the region emptying its
water in the Indian Ocean, has part of its source in Zambia and
forms boders with Namibia, Botswana and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister denied that Zambia is frustrating
regional cooperation in the water sector by dragging its feet
over the signing of the protocol.
</P>
<P>
The water protocol was signed by almost all SADC member states
at last year's summit in Johannesburg, but Zambia pleaded that it
needed more time to study the protocol.
</P>
<P>
The protocol gives guidelines on the utilization of shared
waterways and lakes in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
