<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1630 GMT, April 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- After a two-day marathon meeting in Luxembourg,
agriculture ministers from 15 European Union(EU) nations finally
agreed early today on a plan to resolve the mad cow crisis
threatening the beef industry in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, cattle aged over 30 months in Britain will
be slaughtered and their carcasses will be incinerated.
</P>
<P>
The EU will meet 70 percent of the estimated cost -- 160
million ECUs (about 210 million U.S. dollars) -- of buying cattle
suspected of being infected with the deadly disease, and Britain
will bear the remaining 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A top U.S. military officer has reassured that
the 17,000-strong American peace implementation troops will pull
out of Bosnia at the end of this year on schedule and they will
not pursue suspected war criminals during their stay there.
</P>
<P>
"I'm absolutely convinced that America will not participate
with military forces in Bosnia after the conclusion of this year,"
U.S. Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff John Shalikashvili said
at lunch with Washington Post editors and reporters on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot imagine circumstances changing in such a way that we
would remain in Bosnia," he added.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- At least 13 people have been confirmed dead and 45
others injured when a South Korean inter-city bus plunged into the
Namhan River near Yangpyong city about 40 kilometers west of Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The bus, carrying some 60 people, including students and
shoppers returning from the market, fell into the icy river around
5:30 p.m. local time, a police spokesman was quoted as saying by
reports reaching here. 
</P>
