<HEADLINE> Russia, Poland to Resume Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Pavel
Grachev and his visiting Polish counterpart, Stanislaw Dobrzanski,
have agreed to resume military cooperation between their two
countries but were divided over the issue of NATO's expansion.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference today after their talks, Grachev
said that the resumption of military cooperation is a big step
forward since 1993 when it was scaled down substantially following
Poland's application for NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
He said that a joint team of experts would be set up to make
detailed plans for military cooperation, which will include joint
military exercises in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Poland had also offered Russia the use of its naval facilities
in exchange for Russian military equipment, a proposal yet to be
further consulted between the two sides, Grachev said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of NATO's eastward expansion, the two sides were
as divided as ever.
</P>
<P>
Grachev acknowledged that Poland has the right to apply to join
NATO, but at the same time warned that Russia would reconsider its
military partnership with Poland once it joins the Western
alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
