<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Private Spending, Income Up in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Consumer spending in the U.S.
rebounded strongly in February while personal incomes were also
up, the U.S. Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the consumer spending shot up 1.1
percent after falling 0.4 percent in January. It was the steepest
gain since a 1.7 percent surge in February 1994.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending--two-thirds of the nation's economic
activity--totaled 5.07 trillion dollars at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate, up from 5.01 trillion in January.
</P>
<P>
Spending on durable goods increased at an annual rate of 28.7
billion dollars while those on nondurable goods and services were
up 3.5 billion and 23.6 billion respectively.
</P>
<P>
Still, many analysts expect spending to remain sluggish this
year because of weak income growth, large debt accumulations and
worries over the health of the economy.
</P>
<P>
In February, personal incomes in U.S. grew 0.8 percent to an
annual rate of 6.3 trillion dollars compared with a small 0.1
percent increase in January. The February growth was the largest
since January 1995, when it was 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The increase of personal income was mainly due to a sharp gain
of employment. The U.S. Labor Department reported earlier that
payrolls, which plunged by 188,000 in January, shot up by 705,000
in February.
</P>
<P>
Disposable income--income after taxes--jumped 0.7 percent, up
from an anemic 0.2 percent gain in January and matching December's
advance.
</P>
<P>
The combination of incomes and spending means that Americans'
saving rate--savings as a percentage of disposable income-- was
4.8 percent, down from 5.2 percent a month earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK, Japan to Exchange Trade Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Japan have agreed to
exchange senior officials to help forge closer trade relations
between the two countries, it was reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese recruit has already been chosen and will arrive in
London in June for a two-year stay, and an official of Britain's
department of trade and industry (DTI), yet to be selected, will
go to Tokyo later this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese official will be appointed to what is being
described as a senior management position within the DTI's
automotive directorate, a manufacturing sector in which the UK
wants to improve its trading performance with Japan.
</P>
<P>
He will also participate in an analysis of the effectiveness of
UK automotive trade associations, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was part of the DTI's effort to step up exports
to Japan which is seen here as the most important country in
Britain's drive to develop its trade relations with Asia.
</P>
<P>
Last year, UK exports to Japan rose by 26 per cent to 3.8
billion pounds (5.2 billion US dollars), but Japanese exports to
the UK rose to 9.6 billion pounds (14.4 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ian Lang, Britain's trade and industry secretary, said
yesterday that Britain wanted to raise its exports to Japan to 5
billion pounds (7.5 billion US dollars) by 1997-98. The DTI has
already appointed nine export promoters to help UK companies.
</P>
<P>
Lang is to pay a four-day visit to Japan from April 9 to 12. He
will be accompanied by representatives of more than 100 UK
businesses, the biggest ever trade mission to Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
