<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Reassures Its Troops Pullout from Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A top U.S. military officer has
reassured that the 17,000-strong American peace implementation
troops will pull out of Bosnia at the end of this year on schedule
and they will not pursue suspected war criminals during their stay
there.
</P>
<P>
"I'm absolutely convinced that America will not participate
with military forces in Bosnia after the conclusion of this year,"
U.S. Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff John Shalikashvili said
at lunch with Washington Post editors and reporters on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot imagine circumstances changing in such a way that we
would remain in Bosnia," he added.
</P>
<P>
Shalikashvili made the comment when Bosnian authorities and
West European nations have been calling on the United States to
keep the American ground forces longer than planned in the
war-torn former Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO forces' success so far in enforcing an end to
the fighting in Bosnia has fortified the Clinton administration's
resolve to withdraw the American troops by December.
</P>
<P>
But delays in assembling the civilian reconstruction effort,
and concerns about the need to resettle hundreds of thousands of
refugees and remove millions of land mines, have generated
warnings from local authorities and some European officials that
the fragile Bosnian peace could collapse without the presence
beyond December of at least a residual NATO force.
</P>
<P>
Shalikashvili made clear that the American troops would not
expand their mission from military tasks into searching for any of
the more than 50 Serbs, Muslims and Croats wanted by the
International War Crimes Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Recalling failed efforts by U.S. forces in Somalia to hunt down
a Mogadishu warlord, the General said, "I still have ringing in my
ears" the charges of "mission creep" leveled against American
authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0065 </DOCNO>
