<HEADLINE> Chen Yan, Gold Medal Hopeful at Atlanta Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 3 (Xinhua/OANA) -- As a talented budding star,
Chen Yan is tipped to be a gold medal hopeful at the Atlanta
Olympic Games, said Chinese swimming coach Zhou Ming here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Chen Yan is one of the talented swimmers in the world, such as
Hungarian Krisztina Egerszegi," said the vice head coach of the
Chinese swimming squad.
</P>
<P>
Chen, 16, from Liaoning province, savored her third crown by
swirling ahead in the 400-meter freestyle finals tonight, becoming
the most prolific gold medalist at the current week-long Chinese
Swimming Champions' Tourney.
</P>
<P>
The teenager bagged two golds early in the 400-meter individual
medley on Monday and the 200-meter freestyle on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"She is so clever that she can catch what the coach says very
quickly," exclaimed Zhou who has trained the 1.78-meter girl for
one year, "Nowsdays, it's seldom to meet such talented swimmer."
</P>
<P>
In Zhou's view, Chen was a all-around swimmer and one of the
most promising budding stars in China.
</P>
<P>
"She will be a sensation after improving her breaststroke with
more international experiences," Zhou predicted.
</P>
<P>
Without hesitation, coach Han Binyan also hailed Chen for her
great success made at the Tianjin tourney.
</P>
<P>
"I'm satisfied with her performance," Han said, "The freestyles
will be her strongest disciplines, especially the middle and
long-distance ones."
</P>
<P>
Chen began to splash in the swimming pool at the age of six and
was enrolled into the national squad in 1993. She accumulated
three golds at the Urban Games in Nanjing, Jiangsu province, last
October.
</P>
<P>
Aiming to test her prowess, Chen was competing in as many
events as she can in the tourney, namely the 200-meter, 400-meter
individual medley, 200-meter, 400-meter and 800-meter freestyles.
</P>
<P>
"Although she is also very powerful in the 200-meter backstroke
she decided to give it up due to tight schedule," Han explained.
</P>
<P>
After the national tourney, Chen will tour to Bangkok for the
Asian Championships later.
</P>
<P>
"I want her to compete in more events in Tianjin so that she
can hold on and perform better in the Championships," Han said.
</P>
