<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Farm Ministers Reach Agreement on Mad Cow Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- After a two-day marathon meeting
in Luxembourg, agriculture ministers from 15 European Union(EU)
nations finally agreed early today on a plan to resolve the mad
cow crisis threatening the beef industry in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, cattle aged over 30 months in Britain will
be slaughtered and their carcasses will be incinerated.
</P>
<P>
The EU will meet 70 percent of the estimated cost -- 160
million ECUs (about 210 million U.S. dollars) -- of buying cattle
suspected of being infected with the deadly disease, and Britain
will bear the remaining 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Britain will bear the cost of slaughtering and incinerating the
cattle alone, according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The British government has calculated that it may have to kill
some 15,000 cattle aged over 30 months a week for five or six
years to eradicate the disease, Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy
(BSE).
</P>
<P>
The agreement also requires Britain to present the European
Commission (EC) with a plan on the obligatory slaughter of animals
and/or herds identified as most likely to have been exposed to
BSE-infected meat and bone meal.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here today, European Agriculture
Commissioner Franz Fischler warned that "any lingering doubt
regarding the United Kingdom program will seriously jeopardize the
early abolition of the UK beef export restriction and undermine
consumer confidence-building actions.
</P>
<P>
"Conditions are now right for the restoration of consumer
confidence in beef throughout the EU," he said.
</P>
<P>
The measures already in place and those to be adopted will
guarantee that consumers will be able to buy safe beef, he added.
</P>
<P>
The EU has imposed a world-wide ban on British beef following
Britain's announcement last month of a possible link between the
mad cow disease and its fatal human equivalent, Creutzfeldt-Jakob
Disease.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture ministers' marathon bargaining session, which
began on Monday, was an attempt to reassure consumers that eating
beef would not give them the human version of the incurable
disease.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, British Farm Minister Douglas Hogg attacked
the failure to lift the ban on British beef, which he said was
unjustified.
</P>
<P>
Britain wanted the ban to be lifted by the end of April, but
the final text of the meeting signaled only a review of the ban
within six weeks of when it was originally imposed at the end of
March.
</P>
<P>
Of the EU's 15 members, Britain has the worst record on BSE,
registering 200 or so new cases of the brain infection in cattle
each week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
