<HEADLINE> Palestinian Council Meets In Ramallah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Council (PC)
met this morning in Ramallah for a two-day session, the first to
be held in the West Bank, amidst of a crisis between the
Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat flew by
helicopter to Ramallah from Gaza to attend the meeting. High on
the agenda are issues of the continued closure imposed by Israel
on the Palestinian territories, economic hardships and the new
move proposed by Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres on holding a
referendum on the final status negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Characterizing the situation, Arafat told reporters prior to
the meeting that "there is a very serious situation" in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip and "it is really a disaster."
</P>
<P>
In reaction to Peres' proposal on the referendum, PC
President Abu Ala said that the Palestinians will hold a
referendum of their own on a permanent agreement with Israel.
It will be conducted in the West Bank, Gaza Strip and among
Palestinians living abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians will plan to set up a Palestinian state with
Jerusalem as its capital and to form a confederation with Jordan,
Abu Ala said.
</P>
<P>
With the session in progress, hundreds of Palestinian students
from from Bir Zeit, An-Najah and Bethlehem universities
gathered to protest against Palestinian police harassment.
</P>
<P>
They accused Palestinian security forces of complicity in
Israel's unacceptable violation of the Oslo peace accords. After
warning shots from the police and scuffles, Arafat met with the
students to allow them to speak out their grievances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
