<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Denies Child Labor in Producing Sports Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani manufacturers of
sports goods have strongly refuted allegations of child and bonded
labor in their industry, the official Associated Press of Pakistan
(APP) said today.
</P>
<P>
Football manufacturers in Sailkot, the manufacturing center of
sports goods in Pakistan, denounced the allegations as groundless
and said they were designed to defame the football industry of the
city.
</P>
<P>
The businessmen said the allegations were part of "malicious
propaganda" initiated by some unnamed countries.
</P>
<P>
They said Pakistan's law against child labor is very strict and
it is impossible for them to use child labor.
</P>
<P>
The concept of bonded labor in Pakistan is also a creation by
some countries, which is being used to misguide business circles
in the world, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to an APP survey, the stitching of international
standard footballs is a tough and highly technical job entailing
much more power, force and stamina than children can afford.
</P>
<P>
The survey found workers engaged in stitching footballs in
Sailkot were aged between 25 and 35.
</P>
<P>
Sailkot has enjoyed international repute for quality and
standard sports goods and surgical instruments for more than a
century, the APP reported.
</P>
<P>
As a 100-percent export-oriented city, Sailkot is exporting
sports goods and other products to more than 80 countries in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The businessmen said they were honored that Sailkot footballs
were used in the last Football World Cup.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
