<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spring Sowing Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- South China has finished work on
early rice seedlings and has begun to transplant them, while on
the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River, the growing of
early rice seedlings is going well.
</P>
<P>
The northern and the northwestern parts of the country, which
have been arid during the past seasons, are striving to provide
more water for wheat growing, and the northeast's four provinces
have entered busy spring plowing season.
</P>
<P>
According to an agriculture official, conditions this year are
better than in previous years, with a series of policies
encouraging farming having taken effect.
</P>
<P>
The amount of acreage planted last autumn and winter in China
was nearly 30 million ha, 400,000 ha more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Wheat in the northern part of the country are turning green and
those in the southern part are forming joints, according to the
official, who predicted that the total grain acreage this year
will reach 110 million ha.
</P>
<P>
The official also noted that there are some problems because
drought is still vexing the northern part of the country, while
rain and low temperature are affecting the southern part. Also,
some parts of the country still suffer from shortages of chemical
fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
The official emphasized that a good job must be done in spring
to have a good harvest in the summer and for the whole year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
