<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perry: US to Continue Extending Aid to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry
said here today that the United States will continue to extend aid
to Egypt in the security fields.
</P>
<P>
Perry, who arrived in Egypt Tuesday evening, told reporters
following his meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak that
his country maintains that Egypt plays a key role in achieving a
lasting peace in the Middle East and stability in Africa.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Perry and Mubarak discussed ways in which
Egypt and the U.S. can be more effective in their cooperation for
combating terrorism that is undermining the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Perry also said that they expressed their determination to work
together in order to bring about a comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Perry, who also met with his Egyptian counterpart Mohammed
Hussein Tantawi on boosting bilateral military cooperation, said
he discussed with Mubarak the threats which are targeting the
Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
He said that activating the peace process is difficult, but he
believed that some progress has been made in this regard recently.
</P>
<P>
On U.S.-Egyptian military cooperation, Perry said that the size of
U.S. military aid to Egypt stands at 1.3 billion dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival in Cairo Tuesday, he said that the U.S. would sell
21 new F-16 fighters to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Perry denied reports that the his country and Israel are
working toward a secret defense alliance.
</P>
<P>
Egypt receives 2.1 billion dollars in U.S. aid a year,
second only to Israel's three billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
