<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Denies Inviting Saddam to Habitat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Forein Ministry today
denied a report that Turkish President Suleyman Demirel had
invited Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein to the Second U.N. Conference
on Human Settlements (Habitat 2) scheduled to be held in Istanbul
on June 3-14.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers have reported that Demirel sent an
invitation to Baghdad which would enable the Iraqi leader to
appear at the international platform for the first time since
the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Omer Akbel told a press conference
that President Demirel had sent invitations as the co-host of
Habitat 2 to some heads of state or governments but that no
invitation was extended to Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
In fact, said Akbel, the Iraqi government had officially informed
Ankara that their diplomats based in Turkey would represent
Iraq at the Habitat meeting.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 to 25,000 officials and Non-Government
Organizations (NGO) representatives will attend the two-week event
on urbanization and housing supply processes.
</P>
<P>
Presidents, prime ministers, and other senior government
officials from some countries are expected to attend the
gathering for the last three days of the last large summit of the
century.
</P>
<P>
However, Akble declined to disclose by name the leaders that
have been invited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
