<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Appeals Court Overturns New York Assisted-Suicide Ban
</P>
<P>
A federal appeals court Tuesday struck down New York law making
it a crime for a physician to assist in a suicide, ruling that
terminally ill people have the same right to hasten death by
taking drugs as they do by refusing artificial life supports.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Economy Showing Signs of Pickup in Latest Report
</P>
<P>
Battered recently by storms and undermined for months by weak
sales, the economy has been sluggish for most of the last year.
But figures released Tuesday gave some tentative signs that
business could improve this spring. The index of leading
indicators soared 1.3 percent in February, the biggest jump in 20
years, while business inventories appear to have been drawn down
enough to encourage companies to start increasing production soon.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian Troops Continued Fighting in Chechnya
</P>
<P>
Russian troops continued fighting separatist rebels in several
areas of Chechnya while commanders insisted that they were abiding
by Yeltsin's plan to end the war. The officers said the troops
were only returning fire, though 30 rebels were reported killed in
one battle.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- Hamas Vows New Terror Will Hit Israel
</P>
<P>
Hamas, the Muslim group responsible for 62 deaths in four
recent suicide bombings, said Tuesday it would rekindle its terror
campaign against Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
