<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England Soccer Team Confirms Far East Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The England soccer team
confirmed here on Wednesday its planned trip to the Far East for
matches against the Chinese national eleven and Hong Kong's Golden
Selection side.
</P>
<P>
England will bring a full line-up of about 25 players including
key striker Alan Shearer, newly crowned "Footballer of the Year"
Les Ferdinand and "Gaza" Paul Gascoigne to play the Hong Kong side
in the Century Challenge Cup here.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Hong Kong Golden Selection in association with
Strata Sports Marketing and promoted by ProEvents Management, the
"star-studded" event is expected to be the best international
friendly ever held in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"After playing against Bulgaria last week, Croatia will be our
next opponent on April 24 and then followed by Hungary on May 18,"
said Brian Scott, Travel Manager of the English Football
Association, at a press conference here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Far East trip, during which the England team will compete
against the Chinese side in Beijing on May 23 and then the Golden
Selection on May 26 in Hong Kong, is part of England's warming up
program for June's European Championships in Britain.
</P>
<P>
It will be the team's first visit to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The 25 leading international players in the team will be
fighting for their places in the Euro '96 squad which will be
finalized the day after they return home from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On the team are David Seaman, Tim Flowers, Ian Walker, Gary and
 Philip Neville, Rob Jones, Mark Wright, Steve Howey, Gareth
Southgate, Stuart Pearce, Steve Stone, Ugo Ehiogu, Robert Lee,
Dennis wise, Jamie Redknapp, Paul Gascoigne, Paul Ince, David
Platt, Steve McManaman, Robbie Fowler, Trevor Sinclair, Peter
Beardsley, Nick Barmby, Teddy Sheringham, Les Ferdinand and Alan
Shearer.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people have asked why we'll be rounding off our match
preparation in the Far East. There are several factors,"
explained Scott.
</P>
<P>
"To have stayed home for the last three weeks before the
Championship would have been to risk boredom," he said.
</P>
<P>
To travel out of Europe would also help the team avoid some of
the pressures associated with the Euro '96 tournament as the host
nation, he added.
</P>
<P>
It was the players who decided to take the Far East route
rather than the other two options -- South Africa and North
America, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Sets up Caretaker Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi President Abdur Rahman
Biswas today appointed ten advisers to form a non-party caretaker
government headed by Chief Adviser Habibur Rahman.
</P>
<P>
The newly-appointed advisers are Barrister Ishtiaq Ahmed,
Professor Muhammad Yunus, Professor Md Shamsul Huq, Shequfta Bakht
Chowdhury, Azm Nasiruddin, Maj. Gen. Abdur Rahman Khan, Dr.
Wahiduddin Mahmud, Manzur Elahi, Dr. Najma Chowdhury and Dr.
Jamilurnrzea Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
They will act as ministers and, headed by Chief Adviser
Habibur, oversee the country's next general elections likely to be
held in May.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, President Biswas accepted the resignation of
Prime Minister Khaleda Zia and dissolved the sixth parliament
elected from the February 15 polls which were boycotted by major
opposition parties. Biswas also named Habibur as chief adviser of
the caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
The opposition had been demanding in the last two years the
establishment of a neutral caretaker government to oversee the
country's general elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
