<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Expand Air, Sea, Ground Links with Central Asian States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani said here today that Tehran was interested in
developing air, sea and ground links with the Central Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with visiting Kazakh Foreign Minister Kasm
Zhomarat Tokayev, Rafsanjani said that his country had launched
a massive project to develop the routes to and from Central
Asia.
</P>
<P>
The scheme include establishing large ports in the Caspian
Sea, developing of roads and railroads, building two-way
pipeline between northern and southern Iran for the exportation
and transit of oil via Iran as well as building a
1000-kilometer, two-way railroad between Tehran and Mashhad.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president said that cooperation between Iran,
Russia and other countries in the region played an important
role in establishing peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The long-term and lasting cooperation between Iran, Russia and
other countries, plays a sensitive and important role in
establishing peace and security in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Tehran Radio quoted Tokayev as saying that "Iran
is one of the closest friends of Kazakhstan in the Middle
East because of its important economic and commercial potentials
and because of its rational stance in the international forum."
</P>
<P>
Tokayev conveyed greetings of Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev to Rafsanjani, adding that Nazarbayev was planning to
attend the inauguration ceremony for the opening of the
Mashhad-Sarakhs-Tajan railroad line.
</P>
<P>
The railroad, scheduled to open in mid-May, is planned to
link Central Asia to the Persian Gulf through the Iranian port
city of Bandar Abbas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
