<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBF Announces Eligible Roaster for Atlanta Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Badminton
Federation (IBF) annnouned on Wednesday the roasters of eligible
players who have qualified for the Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
For singles events, 33 players are eligible with 19 pairs in
each of men's and women's doubles, and 17 pairs in mixed doubles,
the IBF said.
</P>
<P>
By the time wild cards and reserve are added to the list, 192
players are expected to participate in Atlanta, with 36 in singles
events and 20 pairs in doubles events.
</P>
<P>
For mixed doubles specialists, it is the first time the event
has been included in the Olympics at Atlanta, the federation said.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Park Joo Bong, who won the first men's doubles
Olympic gold in Barcelona, has come out of retirement to try for
the first mixed doubles gold.
</P>
<P>
With a clear lead at the top of the World Rankings after only
six eligible events, Park and his partner Ra Kyung Min become the
top favorites.
</P>
<P>
In the singles events, Susi Susanti, the Queen of badminton, is
looking to repeat her gold medal performance, as will her fiance
Allan Budi Kusuma.
</P>
<P>
Barcolona was almost a fairytale for Susanti. She and Kusuma
both won the first Olympic golds in the two singles events, and
the first Olympic medals for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Susanti has plans to retire after Atlanta and the couple are
due to be married next year, the IBF said.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, Indonesia's Ardy Wiranata, the Barcelona men's
singles silver medalist, does not qualify even though he is ranked
seventh in the world as a maximum of three players from one
country are eligible in each event. Wiranata is the fourth-highest
Indonesian.
</P>
<P>
Two pairs in the men's doubles, Tony Gunawan/Rudy Wijaya and
Chandra Wijaya/Ade Sutrisna, also have the same problem. They are
ranked seventh and eighth in the world but are the fourth and
fifth Indonesian pairs.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, requirement for a player or pair from each
continent has given the chance to Mauritius' Martine de Souza,
Eddy Clarisse and others to play with the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
The badminton competition at the Olympic Games takes place at
the Georgia State University from July 24 to August 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
