<HEADLINE> 2 Indian Ministers Resign from Rao's Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Two Indian ministers resigned
today out of their disagreement with the high command of the
ruling Congress Party over alliances with local parties and
selection of candidates for the forthcoming general elections
slated to start on April 27.
</P>
<P>
Indian President S.D. Sharma accepted the resignations of
Minister of State for Commerce P. Chidambaram and Minister of
State for Industry M. Arunachalam on the advice of Prime Minister
P.V. Narasimha Rao.
</P>
<P>
Seven other cabinet ministers, including Human Resource
Development Minister M. Scindia, had resigned earlier because of
their involvement in the 18-million-US-dollar hawala scandal,
which was unearthed in January this year.
</P>
<P>
The Congress Party today also announced that rebel leaders and
former ministers Scindia, Chidambaram and Arunachalam were
"automatically" expelled from the party after filing nominations
against the party nominees.
</P>
<P>
Joint Secretary of the All India Congress Committee Ved Prakash
affirmed at a press briefing that anyone who contests against the
official candidates stands automatically expelled from the party.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
