<HEADLINE> Modern Enterprise System Introduced to More Shanghai Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Mayor Xu Kuangdi
announced another 60 enterprises to be used as pilot companies to
experiment with the modern enterprise system, at a special meeting
today.
</P>
<P>
This brings to 200 the total number of pilot enterprises, 80
percent of the city's combined state-owned assets.
</P>
<P>
The modern enterprise system is a major part of the country's
effort to sharpen the competitive edge of state-owned businesses
by requiring them to hold responsible for their own profits and
losses.
</P>
<P>
According to the mayor, the pilot enterprises are to be the
backbone of industry, commerce, agriculture, trade, urban
construction, and transportation in the municipality, China's
largest business center.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the 140 enterprises that were chosen earlier added
five billion yuan in state-owned assets, and had an annual growth
rate of 12.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Huang Ju, secretary of the Municipal Committee of the Communist
Party of China (CPC), told the meeting that Shanghai will try to
get more than two-thirds of its state-owned enterprises operating
within the frame of modern enterprise system in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
