<HEADLINE> Wigan Chairman Arrested in Fraud Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The chairman, director and a player
of Britain's top rubgy club Wigan, were all arrested on Wednesday
on allegation of conspiracy to defraud, police said in Wigan.
</P>
<P>
Detectives from Greater Manchester police arrested chairman
Jack Robinson and director John Martin at their homes after a
local newspaper provided details of its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
The third man arrested was believed to be Wigan's prop forward
Neil Cowie, who is Martin's son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
The investigation reportedly centered on claims of a false
transfer deal involving one of the Superleague club's
international players.
</P>
<P>
Police had been examining several hundred pages of documents,
including some information supplied by the Wigan Observer.
</P>
<P>
In its stories published about one month ago, the Wigan
Observer alleged that Wigan players had been involved in drunken
party in a hotel just before their shock Challenge Cup defeat by
Salford, which caused huge loss to the club.
</P>
<P>
The Rugby Football Leage have launched their own investigation
into the affair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
