<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Rights Subcommission Urged to Avoid Politicization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China and a number of other
countries have urged the U.N. Subcommission on Prevention of
Discrimination and Protection of Minorities to avoid politicizing
its work.
</P>
<P>
"The Subcommission should keep its proceedings away from 'Cold
War' influence in order to uphold the principle of fairness and
objectivity and put an end to unfounded charges against countries
from Asia, Africa and Latin America," Chinese delegate Liu
Xinsheng told the 52nd session of the U.N. Human Rights Commission
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that in international relations there are still
examples of the strong bullying the weak by unilaterally imposing
sanctions and other coercive measures against other countries.
Such acts run counter to the principles of international law
concerning the respect for sovereignty and non-interference in the
internal affairs of others.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, new forms of racism characterized by
xenophobia, discrimination against colored people and migrant
workers are rampant in certain countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
"The various human rights bodies of the United Nations,
including the Subcommission, while keeping acutely aware of the
above-mentioned problems, should give them top priority in
accordance with their respective mandates", Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Indian delegate Hemant Krishan Singh accused the Subcommission
of failing to concentrate its efforts on providing studies and
recommendations on the basis of objective and thorough research.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Subcommission was enthusiastic about
portraying itself as a world human rights inspector rather than
helping every country improve its human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, the Subcommission's fascination with
situations in particular countries was a distortion of its
mandate, as was its preoccupation with passing resolutions which
were fundamentally political acts.
</P>
<P>
"The Subcommission's practice of passing judgement on countries
in a highly selective manner contributed to politicization and
undermined efforts to promote human rights through cooperation,
consensus and dialogue," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Human Rights Commission to give guidance to
the Subcommission, the Commission's only subsidiary body, to
ensure the latter's work complements that of the commission
instead of duplicating it.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistani delegate also pointed out that the Subcommission's
reports and resolutions only targeted weak and small countries
while human rights violations in some major powers had been
ignored. Such a trend had impeded the body from coming up with
fair and valuable advice, he said.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Bangladesh, El Salvador, Russia and
Ukraine echoed the opinion that the Subcommission should be
reformed and its mandate redefined, in order to avoid unfairness
and politicization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0107 </DOCNO>
