<HEADLINE> Australian Airline to Expand Services to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Qantas, an 95-year-old
Australian Airline, announced here today that it will seek the
necessary approvals from the Chinese government to increase the
frequency of its services to China.
</P>
<P>
James Strong, chief executive of the airline, said that the
first phase of the planned expansion would be the introduction of
twice weekly services to Shanghai in late August.
</P>
<P>
He said Qantas will open an office in Shanghai within a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
He said that the airline would also seek approvals to operate
another two weekly services into China by the middle of next year.
</P>
<P>
"This would bring our weekly frequency between the two
countries to four, operating to both Shanghai and Beijing," he
said, adding that it would be a major step towards Qantas'
objective of operating daily flights to the two principal cities
in China as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Qantas operates an extensive network covering 92 destinations,
52 in Australia and 40 overseas, carrying over 16 million
passengers a year in Australia and 25 other countries and regions
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Qantas resumed flying to Beijing in March 1995. 
</P>
