<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3,360 MW Power Generating Capacity Added in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 3,360 megawatts has
been added to Pakistan's Water And Power Development Authority
(WAPDA) power generating capacity in the past three financial
years.
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press of Pakistan reported today this included
1,496 mw hydro-electric and 1,864 mw thermal power generating
capacity.
</P>
<P>
With this addition, WAPDA's total system capacity reached
10,853 mw by the end of June 1995.
</P>
<P>
This represents nearly a 45 percent increase over the system
power generation capacity at the end of June 1992.
</P>
<P>
During the fiscal year from July 1992 to June 1993, a total
addition of 659 mw raised the system capacity to 8,152 mw, 8.8
percent higher than the previous year's total installed generating
capacity.
</P>
<P>
In 1993-94, WAPDA system witnessed a total addition of 1,529 mw
power generating capacity, raising the total system capacity to
9.681 mw, an 18 percent increase over the previous year's total
power generating capacity in WAPDA system.
</P>
<P>
In 1994-95, total addition to WAPDA system stood at 1,172 mw
with the total system generating capacity reached 10,853 mw, a 12
percent increase over the previous year's new power generating
capacity.
</P>
<P>
The total installed power generating capacity in Pakistan is
12,728 mw which consists of 10,853 mw in WAPDA's system, 1,738 mw
in Karachi Electric Supply Corporation and 137 mw from other
sources.
</P>
<P>
A total capacity of 1,634 mw is currently under construction in
two projects of WAPDA, the major power supplier of the country.
</P>
<P>
In the last three years, the Pakistani government emphasizes
energy development to help the country's economic boost.
</P>
<P>
Its open policy regarding investment in power and energy sector
has attracted many foreign companies to invest in the energy
sector.
</P>
<P>
Privatization in the energy sector also helps the development
of power generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
Kot Addu power station, a major power station in central
Pakistan, was privatized Tuesday to a British company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
