<HEADLINE> South Korea Charges Over 450 Election Law Breakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Supreme Public
Prosecutor's Office said that 456 people have been charged with
violating election laws as of today, eight days before the April
11 National Assembly elections.
</P>
<P>
Of the total booked, 131 are running for parliamentary seats
and 57 have been detained.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, 332 people were charged and 18 taken into custody
eight days before the 1992 elections.
</P>
<P>
Of the total number of candidates charged this year, 54 are
from the ruling New Korea Party, 28 from the main opposition
National Congress for New Politics, and 17 each from the United
Liberal Democrats and the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's 15th National Assembly elections will select 299
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
A majority of 253 of them will be elected through direct
popular vote in electoral districts and the remaining 46
uncontested seats will be distributed to parties in proportion to
the number of votes they win in the direct balloting. 
</P>
