<HEADLINE> Iran's Position on Terrorism and Peace Process Remains Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran's position on terrorism and
the Middle East peace process remains unchanged despite the
dialogue with the European Union high-ranking officials, said an
Italian diplomat here today.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat, on condition of anonymity, told Xinhua that the
Iranians did not change their stance toward the issue of the
terrorism and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
But, he declined to specify differences between the two sides
on the crucial issues which affect the future ties between Iran
and the European countries.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat disclosed that the European ambassadors in Tehran
will have a meeting this afternoon and they would adopt a united
stand toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that the embassy would publish an official statement on
the dialogue between the two sides Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Another Western diplomat, who asked not to be identified,
disclosed that today's talks between EU and Iranian officials were
"frank and constructive, but made little progress."
</P>
<P>
The European Union Troika delegation left here for Rome after
dialogue with Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Iran's state-run Tehran Radio claimed this afternoon that the
talks between Troika and Iran for expansion of relations were
"positive."
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said earlier that
Europe should pursue an independent policy in its relations with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
"Relations between Iran and Europe are in the interests of
both sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that dialogue should continue based on mutual respect
and interests.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the Middle East peace process, Velayati said,
the peace process has failed because it has ignored the rights of
the Palestinian nation.
</P>
<P>
Iran gave little publicity to the arrival of the EU delegation
and barred journalists and photographers from approaching the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The delegation took a special flight from Rome and arrived
here Tuesday afternoon. Their stay in Tehran is about 20 hours.
</P>
<P>
Mario Panaro, counselor of the Italian Embassy in Tehran, told
Xinhua that the Troika delegation is headed by Italian Foreign
Ministry Undersecretary Ludovico Incisa di Camerana.
</P>
<P>
The Italian undersecretary is accompanied by Spanish Foreign
Ministry Director General of the Middle Eastern Affairs, Miguel
Angel Moratinos, and Irish Foreign Ministry Director General for
Middle Eastern Affairs, Kenneth Thomson.
</P>
<P>
The Troika visit to Iran is taking place following a decision
made by European foreign ministers in their March 9-10 meeting in
Palermo, Italy.
</P>
<P>
Despite the U.S. pressure, major European countries such as
Germany, France, Italy, Spain and Britain still insist on
dialogue with Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
