<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Boom City Turning Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- An oil boom city that just one and
a half decades ago did not boast a single inch of green space for
its urban residents is blooming.
</P>
<P>
Daqing City in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province has
become increasingly green, thanks to efforts by local authorities.
</P>
<P>
In 1981 the amount of greenland for urban residents was
zero. The city's forest coverage has grown from 1.45 percent in
1981 to 26.1 percent, and greenland per head for urban residents
from zero in 1981 to 4.4 square meters.
</P>
<P>
As part of the city's measures to improve afforestation, local
officials have signed contracts of responsibility for
afforestation.
</P>
<P>
There was only one park for children in the city in 1981. Now
there are 12 parks across the city and trees are widespread in
both residential and industrial areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
