<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Natural Rubber Production Up 8.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's natural rubber
production for January 1996 increased by 8.4 percent to 114,987
tons, compared with to 106,080 tons last December, the country's
statistics department said today.
</P>
<P>
According to its monthly figures released today, the department
said natural rubber exports in January were down by 1,067 tons or
1.3 percent as compared with 81,282 tons in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
In January, Malaysia's natural rubber was mainly exported to
South Korea (10,569 tons), the United States (9,161 tons), Germany
(7,462 tons), Britain (4,132 tons), the Netherlands (3,939 tons)
and Turkey (3,282 tons).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysia's import, which amounted to 32,240 tons,
was mainly from Thailand, the Philippines, Vietnam, Myanmar,
Liberia, the Ivory Coast and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Domestic consumption of natural rubber in January was 28,873
tons, a reduction of 433 tons or 1.5 percent as compared with
29,306 tons in December 1995. But it was up by 3,888 tons or 15.6
percent from 24,985 tons in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
The main consumers of natural rubber in the country were from
the rubber gloves industry (15,683 tons or 54.3 percent), rubber
thread (5,579 tons or 19.7 percent) and tyre and tubes.
</P>
<P>
Stocks of natural rubber at the end of January were 204,786
tons, up 29,235 tons as against 175,551 tons in December last
year. However, there was a drop in stocks of 11,473 tons or 5.3
percent against 216,259 tons held at the end of January last year,
the released added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
