<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Champion Le Praised by Her Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 3 (Xinhua/OANA) -- Zhou Ming, coach of world
champion Le Jingyi, said on Wednesday he was fully satisfied with
Le's performances at the on-going China's Swimming Champions'
Tourney.
</P>
<P>
Despite her failure to win any event so far at the tourney,
"she is launching a strong comeback after a long-period layoff,"
said Zhou, one of four top coaches of the Chinese national squad.
</P>
<P>
Le, women world record holder in both 50-meter and 100-meter
freestyles, was edged by Shan Ying to the second in the 100-meter
freestyle Monday night, and settled for the third place in the
200-meter freestyle Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
In the Tianjin meet which serves as the Olympic trials, Le, a
big shot in the national squad, was competing in the 50-meter,
100-meter and 200-meter freestyles, three individual events as
well as two to three relay events.
</P>
<P>
Under a four-stage pre-Olympic training program starting from
June, 1995 to July of the year, Le has improved stage-by-stage and
"I'm satisfied with her steady progress," said Zhou who started
his stint of national coach in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Being a postgraduate from the Beijing Sports University, Zhou
had coached Olympic champion and world record holder Zhuang Yong
and Yang Wenyi, both retired after the Barcelona Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
To forecast the prospect for the Atlanta Olympics, Zhou said
China is tipped to win medals in the women's freestyles, with the
50-meter and 100-meter events in particular.
</P>
<P>
"At least we are in the same level against the Americans and
the Germans," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhou circled out American veteran Amy Van Dyken and Russian
Natalia Mescheryakova as the most dangerous rivals at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
On the U.S. Olympic trials last March in Indianapolis, Zhou
said those results "were not bad at all."
</P>
<P>
"Though the absolute advantage of the American swimmers is
disappearing, I felt they have a plenty of all-around potentials."
</P>
<P>
"American swimmers are serious gold contenders almost in every
event, and with the home-turf advantage, they may reap a great
success in Atlanta," he said.
</P>
<P>
Richard Quick, coach of the U.S. women's Olympic squad, said
after the U.S. trials that "U.S. women are decided underdogs to
the Chinese and the Australians, we aren't favoured in a single
event."
</P>
<P>
However, Zhou turned down the suggestion, saying that "they are
more clever nowsdays by leaving some leeway in their prediction."
</P>
<P>
"Anyway, the current results reflect nothing about the Olympic
competitions," Zhou said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
