<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IGAD Meets to Revitalize its Function: Kenyan FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Presidents and Prime Ministers of
The Inter-Governmental Authority on Drought and Development met
here last month to revitalize the organization's function,
Kenyan Foreign Minister Stephen Musyoka said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Musyoka said at the summit
which ended on March 22 in Nairobi, they restructured the
organization into the Inter-Governmental Authority on Development
(IGAD) and reached agreement unanimously on basing its
headquarters in Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
"They need to build strong structure in the sub-region and
focus on development", said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He gave the news conference on the IGAD summit, saying he had
found no time last month to brief newsmen on it.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state from Kenya, Uganda, Eritrea and Sudan, Prime
Minister from Ethiopia and the Foreign Minister of Djibouti
attended the two-day summit which also wanted to mediate in the
Sudan's issue.
</P>
<P>
As the relations between Sudan and Ethiopia and betwen Sudan
and Uganda remain tense, it was a good thing for leaders of
all those countries to come together, and if they meet regularly,
they are in a position to settle the disputes between them, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Musyoka said as Sudan insisted that every resolution should be
adopted unanimously, no agreement on Sudan had been passed at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Sudan insisted that she could not track down on the three
suspects who tried to assasinate Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
in Addis Ababa in June last year, he said, noting this was "not
only a crime against Egypt, but a crime against the whole of
Africa."
</P>
<P>
So the leaders at the meeting persisted in asking Sudan to
hand over these suspects, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
In reply to a question, he said he regretted that there are
now conflicts in Somalia, Liberia and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Kenya hopes that there should be stability in Sudan and
Somalia and that nobody is exporting arms to these countries,
Musyoka said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
