<HEADLINE> Manila Closes 266 Establishments for Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 266 establishments in
Metro Manila have been ordered to close down for violations of the
fire and building safety codes while 223 others have been advised
to correct deficiencies, the Department of Interior and Local
Governments said today.
</P>
<P>
It said 139 establishments in the Philippine capital, including
movie houses, shopping malls, restaurants, disco houses, clubs and
schools, have so far been closed.
</P>
<P>
Manila Mayor Alfredo Lim also ordered the closure of 127
boarding houses and dormitories in the university belt for
violations of the fire, building and sanitation codes.
</P>
<P>
The establishments that have been ordered for closure are
dubbed potential fire traps because of lack of emergency exists.
</P>
<P>
Following the Ozone disco tragedy that killed at least 160
people last month, the government ordered the inspection of all
establishments and the immediate closure of the establishments
found to be violating the fire and building safety codes.
</P>
<P>
However, the establishments may reopen upon compliance with the
fire and building codes or after correction of their deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
