<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Malaysian Air Force
today launched an exercise aimed at upgrading the efficiency of
pilots and ground crew in handling combat aircraft, Malaysia's
national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Bernama said the 16-day, three-phase exercise will involve six
jetfighter squadrons based in Kuantan, Labuan and Butterworth.
</P>
<P>
The jetfighter squadrons involved are the British Aerospace
Hawk squadrons, the Northrop F-5E squadrons and the MiG-29N
squadrons, Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted First Division Commander of the Royal
Malaysian Air Force Kol Toh Boon Fook as saying that air-to-air
and air-to-ground firing using training weapons would be launched
during the first phase of the exercise.
</P>
<P>
The air-to-air firing exercise would be the first ever held in
the country, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In the second and third phases, live ammunition, CRV-7 rockets,
500-1b bombs and airfield destruction bombs will be used in
maritime and ground attacks, the report said.  
</P>
