<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM on Sino-Japanese Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen said here today that smooth development of
Sino-Japanese relations depends on Tokyo's attitude towards the
history and the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at a press conference here, Qian stated
that it can be said correct handling of the above two issues
constituted the primary political foundation for the normalization
of diplomatic relations between the two east Asian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Qian said, only a correct recognition of the history can
open up the future of bilateral relations. With regard to the
Taiwan issue, Japan should also maintain an unmistakable attitude
so that relations can be developed smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Qian stressed that Taiwan is an inalienable part of China and
that China's policy of peaceful reunification and "one nation, two
systems" has remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the Taiwan Strait, he went on to say, will
become quite normal provided the authorities on Taiwan do not go
in for its independence and foreign forces refrain from supporting
and abetting their secessionist effort.
</P>
<P>
Qian said tha for historical reasons, Japan should understand
China's position on the Taiwan issue better, since it has more
knowledge of the island's history.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Qian also urged the Japanese
government to take earliest possible measures to destroy the
chemical weapons left behind in China by Japanese troops during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived here Sunday for a four-day visit, has met
with Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, Foreign Minister Yikihiko
Ikeda and several other Japanese government officials. He has also
called on Emperor Akihito. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
