<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archives Tell Social Progress in Tibet (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since 1952, the central government has never taken a penny out
of Tibet, but invested 35 billion yuan in various ventures and
causes. Many preferential economic policies for its development
have been also enacted.
</P>
<P>
The archives also contain a report on the way descendants of
blacksmiths were subject to rules which forbid them from certain
things. It says that a man working for the Dalai Lama was expelled
after he was found to be a descendant of a smith.
</P>
<P>
In the past, all blacksmiths, as well as gold and silver
craftsmen, butchers, and their offsprings were the "untouchable",
not allowed to work for the government, and they could not marry
into families of different classes.
</P>
<P>
But today, the descendants of these people are not prejudiced
against any more. Some of them have become government officials,
people's deputies, and members of people's political consultative
conferences.
</P>
<P>
Pugza, son of Tibetan knife maker in Xigaze, said: "In light of
my own family history, Tibetans have never had the human rights
and freedom as they have today, and anyone respecting history and
facts should agree with me."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archives Tell Social Progress in Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Today, rural Tibetan people have an average of 20.36 square
meters of living space, and urban Tibetans 12.59 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The surrounding area of the Potala Palace, where the
"untouchable" were forbidden to dwell in the past, is now home to
a decent "Snow" neighborhood committee of ordinary Tibetan people.
</P>
<P>
But the Dalai clique claims that Tibetan people are "living in
hell" today.
</P>
<P>
Files in the archives said that a nobleman in Xigaze, named
Gedwa, raised tax rates at will, and occupied lands of serfs in
1955, but the Dalai government did nothing to stop him. Many
became broken men because of too heavy taxes, and noblemen used
slaves to pay for their debts.
</P>
<P>
Another document shows that in 1944, every resident of Zheku
had to hand in the wool of 20 sheep for Dalai's clothes, and wool
of 12 sheep for his hat, but they got little payment.
</P>
<P>
Dunzhu, vice-chairman of the government of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, said that the Chinese government has given top priority to
solving the problem of food and clothes for all the Tibetan people
in the past several decades.
</P>
<P>
All the arable land, pasture, forest and most of the livestock,
owned only by high-ranking religious and governmental officials
and noblemen before 1959, were redistributed to serfs, who
accounted for 95 percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
In the past decades, the Central government has adopted a
rehabilitation policy towards Tibet, and decided to exempt its
agricultural taxes until the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Those who have visited the Potala Palace will find that all the
halls and rooms, including Dalai's sleeping room and scripture
reciting halls, have been renovated as new.
</P>
<P>
In fact the central government did the work for the betterment
of its religious policies. It has allocated 216 million yuan (25.4
million US dollars) to repair the Potala Palace, the Jakong
Monastery, and many other religious buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archives Tell Social Progress in Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- For the scripture-chanting ceremony
marking the Dalai Lama's birthday, "a set of intestines, two
heads, bowls of blood and a complete human skin are urgently
needed. Please send them here immediately."
</P>
<P>
This was written in a letter by a Tibetan official to a tribal
head in the 1950s, before the region was peacefully liberated.
</P>
<P>
The letter is now kept intact in the Archives of the Tibet
Autonomous Region here. The archives, built in the 1960s, preserve
over three million historical documents on Tibet dating from the
Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368) to the 1950s, and it is one of the local
archives with the richest amount of historical data in the country.
</P>
<P>
An expert with the Archives explained that before 1959 it was
common for the Dalai Lamas to use parts of human bodies for their
religious activities.
</P>
<P>
The files also indicate that slave trading was rampant at that
time.
</P>
<P>
"After reading the decrees here, no one can believe that 'the
Tibetan people enjoyed freedom and happiness' under the Dalai
Lama, as he has been preaching outside China," the expert said.
</P>
<P>
According to the archives, of the one million people in Tibet
in 1950 over 900,000 had no homes of their own. And over 1,000
beggar families lived in the open air on the streets of Lhasa,
whose total population was only 20,000 at that time.
</P>
<P>
"Only after Tibet was liberated and the central government
built rows of houses in Lhasa's Lubo district did the homeless for
the first time have their own shelters," 60-year-old local
resident Chaka said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ends Dialogue with Iran on Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- An European Union Troika
delegation left here for Libya after dialogue with Iran on
crucial issues of terrorism and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The EU delegation held talks with Iranian Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati this morning on the two issues which would decide
the future ties between Iran and European countries.
</P>
<P>
But both sides refrained from making any comments on the
results of the negotiations at this moment.
</P>
<P>
Iran gave little publicity to the arrival of the EU delegation
and barred journalists and photographers from approaching the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The opposition daily Salam today published a commentary
criticizing the dialogue between Tehran and the EU, terming it a
"one-way dialogue" by Europe "in order to put pressure on the
national and religious sanctities of the Islamic Iran."
</P>
<P>
"In the critical, one-way dialogue of Europe against Iran, it
is always their demands and impositions which are discussed," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The delegation took a special flight from Rome and arrived
here Tuesday afternoon. Their stay in Tehran is about 20 hours.
</P>
<P>
Tehran is the first leg of the EU delegation, which will also
go to Syria, Lebanon, Egypt and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Mario Panaro, Counsellor of the Italian Embassy in Tehran, told
Xinhua that the Troika delegation is headed by Italian Foreign
Ministry Undersecretary Ludovico Incisa di Camerana.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the visit by the EU delegation is
crucial for the relations between Iran and the European
countries, which is seeking to persuade the Iranian authorities
to unequivocally condemn terrorism and disassociate themselves
from terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Undersecretary is accompanied by Spanish Foreign
Ministry Director General of the Middle Eastern Affairs Miguel
Angel Moratinos and Irish Foreign Ministry Director General for
Middle Eastern Affairs Kenneth Thomson.
</P>
<P>
The Troika visit to Iran is taking place following a decision
made by European foreign ministers in their March 9-10 meeting in
Palermo, Italy.
</P>
<P>
Despite U.S. pressure, major European countries such as
Germany, France, Italy, Spain and Britain still insist on
dialogue with the Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani in a press
conference held in middle of this month expressed his welcome
to the visit of the EU delegation, saying "we are ready to
hold talks with them."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "there is no need for the Europeans to
take the pains of traveling to the country. Theoretically
speaking, we do not agree with what is going on now under
the title of peace, because this peace is not just, as the
rights of the Palestinians are being trampled."
</P>
<P>
But he pledged that "we will create no stumble blocks."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of terrorism, he said, "in principle, we oppose
any terrorist act from anyone and any side."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "as a Palestinian movement struggling to
liberate its country, the Hamas should not be condemned."
</P>
<P>
"But if a terrorist activity is carried out, it should
not be accepted." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
