<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Enjoys Rapid Power Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 3 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region has become an important power production base in
China and the largest power supplier to Beijing, capital of the
country, power industry sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The region provided over 900,000 kwh of electricity for Beijing
in the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
During the Eighth Five-Year Plan period (1991-1995), the state
invested a total of 11 billion yuan in developing the power
industry in the region, and built a group of power plants with a
total generating capacity of 1.76 million kw. The Fengzhen Power
Plant is the first power plant in the country's ethnic minority
regions, which has a generating capacity of one million kw..
</P>
<P>
Local statistics showed that by the end of 1995, the installed
generating capacity of the region had topped 5.86 million kw, up
52 percent than the 1990 figure.
</P>
<P>
According to the director of the Inner Mongolia Power
Administration, the region is in the forefront of the country in
terms of per capita installed generating capacity and power
output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
