<HEADLINE> Central Government Helping Tibet to Eliminate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China's central government is doing
its utmost to aid the Tibet Autonomous Region eliminate poverty,
according to a senior government official.
</P>
<P>
Yang Song, vice-chairman of the regional government, made the
remark in a meeting yesterday with Arthur Holcomb, representative
of the United Nations Development Program in China.
</P>
<P>
Holcomb and his assistants are here, discussing projects to aid
the poor and protect natural reserves with local government
departments.
</P>
<P>
Yang told the visitors that 75 percent of Tibetans have risen
above the poverty line over the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
"The Tibet regional government has drawn up a plan to help the
remaining 25 percent of residents eliminate poverty over the next
five years," he said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, Tibet must accelerate growth of the farming sector
and the energy, transport and telecommunications industries, as
well as such sectors as education, culture, science and public
health, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Over the next five years the central government will earmark at
least 10 billion yuan for Tibet, and urge other parts of the
country to provide two billion yuan in assistance.
</P>
<P>
"All international organizations, including the United Nations
and foreign governments, are welcome to provide aid to Tibet
without any conditions attached," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Holcomb praised the Chinese government for
having done a great deal of work to reduce the number of Tibetans
living under the poverty line and expand production in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that the Tibet regional government is
fully capable of eliminating poverty among Tibetans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
