<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control on IC Card Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China has taken measures to curb
the overlap in Intelligence Card (IC) production across the
country, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to a circular issued by the Ministry of Electronics
Industry (MEI) here today, all new projects in relation with IC
production must seek the approval of the MEI and relevant
departments beforehand.
</P>
<P>
No IC card, floppy disc drive or software, whether imported
from abroad and made in China, will be allowed to be sold on the
market before undergoing quality checks by state designated
quality control departments.
</P>
<P>
ICs, popularly known as "electronic money", are necessary
accessories of China's "Golden Card Project".
</P>
<P>
A national estimate showed that the annual demand for ICs in
China will be 15 million before the year 2000. However, IC
production lines across the country have a combined production
capacity of more than 100 million a year, causing a huge waste in
material and foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The MEI said in a circular titled "The Golden Card Project"
that this sector should be subject to a unified scheme in
planning, manufacture, distribution and management.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 232 Million Dollar Remittance Racket Unearthed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A massive racket involving
remittances of over 8,000 million rupees (232 million US dollars)
in the guise of payment for import has been unearthed in India.
</P>
<P>
The racket was being operated with the connivance of officials
of nationalized and foreign banks, highly-placed sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The deep-rooted network, involving employees of the State Bank
of Bikaner and Jaipur, United Commercial Bank (UCO Bank), South
Indian Bank and Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation, had
siphoned off hundreds of crores (one crore equals 10 million) in
foreign exchange to Hong Kong, Singapore and Dubai and other tax
havens since 1991.
</P>
<P>
In a Mumbai (Bombay) branch of UCO Bank, nearly 1,500 million
rupees (43.48 million US dollars) were deposited in cash in the
account of a "bogus firm" floated by a Mumbai-based company
secretary, without the bank manager questioning the source of the
money. Banks are not allowed to accept deposits in cash which are
more than 50,000 rupees (1,449.28 dollars), the same sources said.
</P>
<P>
The entire amount of money was remitted abroad through Hong
Kong bank subsequently. Seven persons, including a manager of
State Bank of Bikaner and Jaipur and the manager and chief cashier
of the UCO Bank branch, were arrested for their alleged
involvement in the transaction.
</P>
<P>
Connivance of employees of some banks in New Delhi, capital of
India, in such illegal foreign exchange transactions in huge
quantities has been established, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
