<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM: Jordan Can Provide Equilibrium for Final Israeli-Palestinian Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister Ehud Barak
has said that the establishment of "some sort of an affiliation"
between Jordan and the Palestinian territories would help provide
a "stable equilibrium" for the final Israeli-Palestinian
settlement.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Jordan Times at his office Tuesday, Barak
said that it was "up to the Jordanians and the Palestinians
themselves to decide the kind of affiliation they want through a
dialogue that runs parallel to final status talks between Israel
and the Palestinians."
</P>
<P>
The former Israeli army chief-of-staff also said that the
month-old Israeli blockade of the West Bank and Gaza Strip was
aimed at reducing the dependency of the Palestinian economy on
Israel in addition to the security considerations related to
stopping suicide bombings against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Israel would not negotiate with the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas), because that would result in the
"emergence of more extremist groups."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Israel would not oppose the participation
of Hamas in the Palestinian political system, provided the
Palestinian National Authority crushed the "terrorist elements
within Hamas."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government, he added, was not imposing
preconditions for resuming negotiations with either Lebanon or
Syria, but that his country "expects a clear Syrian condemnation
of the terrorist attacks."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Iraq, Barak said that the international embargo
imposed on Iraq "should continue until the present regime is
replaced by a more reasonable one." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
