<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 09:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Readjusts Budget for Fiscal 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Cabinet has approved the
latest budget for the 1997 fiscal year, with more emphasis on
investment, education and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The budget approved on Tuesday still totaled 979 billion baht
(39.2 billion U.S. dollars), up 16.1 percent over the 1996 fiscal
year and unchanged in comparison with the previous version
approved on February 13, but it has been restructured.
</P>
<P>
The revised budget raised its spending on investment to 417.3
billion baht (16.7 billion dollars) from 328.4 billion baht (13.1
billion dollars) set in the previous version, according to the
Budget Bureau under the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
General administrative expenditures were cut by 6.1 percent in
the new budget to 537.2 billion baht (21.5 billion dollars) from
572.1 billion baht (22.9 billion dollars) set in the February 13
version to ease the country's current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
The education sector received 21.8 percent of the budget, the
largest portion compared with other sectors, while the Ministry of
Science, Technology and Environment saw the highest budget
increase at 31.7 percent in percentage terms, although its share
of the total of the budget was as small as 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The spending on debt services was down 27 percent to 24.5
billion baht (980 million dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
