<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 08:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Raises Fuel Prices by 50 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran today increased its domestic
oil prices between 30 to 50 percent amid fears that the price hike
might further increase the 100-percent inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Today's local dailies carried an announcement on the price
increase by the government-owned National Company for Refining
and Distribution of Oil Products.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said the price increase will be effective
today "to protect the national assets and non-renewable energies."
</P>
<P>
It added that the law governing the Second Development Plan
approved by the Iranian Parliament mandated that every year the
subsidies for oil would be gradually eliminated.
</P>
<P>
Under a spring downpour this morning, Tehran residents pulled
into a gas station in northern Tehran to fill up the tank. Most of
them were unaware of the price increase.
</P>
<P>
A gas station attendant told Xinhua that because the
announcement was not well publicized, most drivers did not know
about the price increase.
</P>
<P>
"The announcement was made Tuesday night. It could have been
made earlier to avoid the problems we have today," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that instead of arguing with customers, he showed them
the large poster on the wall of the gas station. The poster
listed the new prices under the red emblem of the National
Company for Refining and Distribution of Oil Products.
</P>
<P>
An employee working for the Ministry of Culture and Islamic
Guidance who spoke on condition of anonymity said that the price
increase would have an adverse effect on ordinary people's
purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
"The government increases its prices. The retailers follow by
increasing their prices. The real victims here are the ordinary
people, the clerks working for the government and private firms,
those on a fixed salary," he added.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the government for not increasing the salaries
of the civil service employees to keep up with the inflation
rate.
</P>
<P>
The oil prices in oil-rich Iran are still the lowest in the
world. Even with the price increase, a gallon of regular gasoline
would cost about 600 rials (or about 20 U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
But economic observers here have noted that the price hike
would boost the inflation rate. The official figures put the
inflation rate at 60 percent but observers say that the inflation
is about 100 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
