<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 08:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist's Sandstorm Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The memories of a severe sandstorm
that hit northwestern parts of China almost a year ago are still
vivid for many people.
</P>
<P>
The storms, in May 1995, caused direct economic losses of up to
560 million yuan. Scientists in China have been researching into
whether such great losses can be reduced.
</P>
<P>
Young scientist Yan Xiangkui and his colleagues have now come
up with ways of fighting back against the storms.
</P>
<P>
They concluded after careful research that stubble and unplowed
farm fields can effectively resist sand and dust storms.
</P>
<P>
They realized that sandstorms normally occurred during spring
when the farmland is naked, and the trees are still bare,
resulting in strong winds being able to blow away surface soil,
fertilizers or even seeds and seedlings.
</P>
<P>
With the loss of erosive surface soil, and organic substances,
the land gradually becomes desertified.
</P>
<P>
In other countries where wind erosion is severe, the land along
wind line is never plowed, and some crop stubble is kept to resist
wind erosion.
</P>
<P>
Yan's method is that stubble is to be kept in harvested fields,
unplowed intervals are allowed between plowed land, and the two
interchange periodically. The interval is planted with forage
grass, small fruit trees, or other crops that can be used
medically.
</P>
<P>
Research shows that the stubble and unplowed belt inside
farmland can not only resist wind and sand, it can also help to
keep water, and stabilize soil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0181 </DOCNO>
