<HEADLINE> Daily Currency Transaction Down 21 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The daily currency transaction on
the Shanghai-based China Foreign Exchange Trade System in March
was down 21 percent from February to 214 million US dollars, a
system spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the drop was due to the experimentation
of the foreign exchange surrender system among foreign-funded
enterprises in Shanghai, Jiangsu Province, and Shenzhen and Dalian
cities. Under the surrender system, foreign-funded enterprises can
buy foreign exchange directly from designated banks.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4.5 billion US dollars-worth of foreign exchange
changed hands last month, according to the spokesman, who also
said that the total foreign exchange trading volume in the first
quarter broke down to 13.93 billion US dollars, 8.61 billion
Hong Kong dollars and 20.7 billion Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The US currency continued its upward trend against the
yuan last month, with its average trade-weighted value rising from
8.321 yuan at the end of February to 8.3339 on March 29, the last
trading day of the month. Its monthly high was 8.3365 yuan. The
greenback's rise in March was 128 points, up 55 points from
February.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar was largely stable last month, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen retreated against the local currency by 1,015
points last month, compared with a rise of 1,922 points in
February. It was quoted at 100 yen to 7.8276 yuan at the end
of March.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the US unit, the Hong Kong dollar and the yen are
the only three currencies traded on China's national foreign
exchange market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
