<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 08:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Guess Who's Coming to Dinner? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese farmer Gu Yingming could
hardly believe his eyes when an unexpected guest arrived at his
humble home in northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
His excited mother quickly hurried to the kitchen to find some
food for their special guest.
</P>
<P>
They were playing host to Maomao, a fully grown giant panda,
who just strolled into their home in Jiuchi Village, in the
township of Maoping.
</P>
<P>
Local people call the rare animal "Maomao", and they have
become used to seeing the animal move freely around the village.
</P>
<P>
But it was the first time that Maomao directly entered a
farmer's house.
</P>
<P>
"I was both surprised and excited to find my special guest
pushing open my house's door in the evening," said Gu Yingming,
head of the village, "Seeing our respectable guest coming, my
mother hurried to find a dinner for him."
</P>
<P>
After eating some meat, Maomao found a pail of honey by
himself, and had another feast. Later he walked into the cattle
pen and fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
The next day Maomao paid visits to other households in the
village, by knocking their windows or doors, and he spent most of
the day eating bamboo shoots in the bamboo forest in front of Gu
Yingming's home.
</P>
<P>
When night was coming, he suddenly appeared at one villager's
kitchen room, eating rice from a pot.
</P>
<P>
On the third day, Maomao seemed to be in low spirit and
couldn't eat much. Medical staff from the provincial animal
protection department rushed to the village, and sent the precious
animal to the rare animal breeding center to recuperate.
</P>
<P>
On the day Maomao was leaving, all the villagers held torches
to see him off.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time for us to have such an intimate
relationship with a giant panda, we are all unwilling to part with
him," said Gu Yingming.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1,000 giant pandas living in China, more than
160 of them are living in the Hanzhong Prefecture of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province. And on March 23 the giant panda visited
the Jiuchi Village of Maoping township in this region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
