<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 08:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian FM to Visit Southeast Asian Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The newly-elected Coalition
Government of Australia launched its first wave of overseas
diplomatic campaign as Minister for Foreign Affairs Alexander
Downer announced today that he would visit three Southeast Asian
countries later this month.
</P>
<P>
The first overseas visit by high-ranking officials of the new
Government followed a long-awaited visit to Australia by Malaysian
leader Mahathir Mohamad last week.
</P>
<P>
Downer will visit Indonesia from 15 to 18 April, Singapore from
18 to 20 April and Thailand from 20 to 22.
</P>
<P>
His Southeast Asian tour is part of the major gesture that the
Coalition Government made to assure its Asian neighbors of its
commitment to the region. At the completion of Downer's
three-nation visit, the Australian Government will have official
talks with four of the most influential members of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) within six weeks after it took
office.
</P>
<P>
"The regional destinations I have chosen clearly reflect that
closer engagement with Asia will be this Government's highest
foreign policy priority," he said.
</P>
<P>
Downer is seen to pave the way for Australian Prime Minister
John Howard to pay his first visit overseas, possibly as early as
in June. Howard has promised in the election campaign that his
first overseas visit will be to a Southeast Asian nation.
Indonesia is predicted to be on top of Howard's list of
destinations, because Indonesian leader Suharto has formally
invited Howard to visit the country.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia is a natural first overseas destination and reflects
the priority the Government will be giving to the relationship
with Indonesia," Downer said in a news release today.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that improvement of bilateral relations with
the three nations were the top target of his visit.
</P>
<P>
He said that Australia and Singapore enjoyed "excellent"
relations across the board. He also said that Australia would
further improve the "very well-developed" relationship with
Thailand, which Australia saw as a "very important regional
partner."
</P>
<P>
The Coalition Government has adopted a foreign policy that is
perceptibly different from that of the previous Labor Government.
While maintaining consistence in Australia's commitment to
multi-national forums such as the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) group, the Coalition Government attaches great
importance to the development of bilateral relations with
individual members of regional blocs.
</P>
<P>
It has adopted a more flexible attitude toward involvement in
multi-national organizations. For example, Howard told Mahathir
that Australia would continue to develop relationship with
Malaysia despite the fact that it could not join the 10-member
East Asia Economic Caucus (EAEC) that was initiated by Mahathir.
</P>
<P>
Downer will also visit New Zealand and Papua New Guinea after
his Southeast Asia tour.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
