<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Security Officials Hold Secret Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Senior Israeli and Palestinian
security officials, led by General Security Service (GSS) chief
Ami Ayalon and Palestinian Preventive Security chief Mohammed
Dahalan, have held a series of meetings in Gaza recently to
enhance cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According The Jerusalem Post, the latest meeting was at the end
of last week, at the office of Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat. Those attending were Arafat,
Ayalon, Dahalan and Palestinian police chief Razi Jabali, the
newspaper quoted both Israeli and Palestinian sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources described the meetings as a direct offshoot of the
Sharm el-Sheikh anti-terror summit last month. CIA officers have
also been present at a number of the meetings, aimed at improving
cooperation between the security forces, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
A senior Israeli security official said the meetings in
themselves reflect a degree of improvement in relations between
the Israeli and Palestinian security services. However, the
official said that "there is still much distrust between the
sides."
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians have an interest today in showing that they
are working to fight terror," said the official. "But we are still
waiting to see the results. When they've caught (Izzadin Kassam
commander Mohammed) Dief and turned him over to us, then we know
that they're for real."
</P>
<P>
Dahalan told the Jerusalem Post that both sides agreed to have
these meetings at the Sharm el-Sheikh summit. He described the
meetings as "productive" and said that the PNA has met most of
Israel's demands for cracking down on Hamas.
</P>
<P>
"We have detained 11 of the 13 persons on the wanted list
given to us by Israel," Dahalan said in a telephone interview
from his Gaza headquarters.
</P>
<P>
He added that his force's interrogation of Hamas detainees has
revealed that a Hamas splinter group has been carrying out terror
attacks independently of Izzadin Kassam, Hamas' military wing,
since September 1993 just after the Oslo Accords were signed.
</P>
<P>
The group is called El Jihaz Al-Sira, or "The Secret
Underground," and is controlled by Hamas officials outside of the
occupied territories, said Dahalan. 70 members of the underground
have been detained in recent weeks, he added.
</P>
<P>
Dahalan strongly denied reports that he was holding secret
talks with Dief before the recent wave of suicide attacks, in
hopes of reaching an agreement between Izzadin Kassam and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Dief, according to Dahalan, has not fled the area and is
likely hiding out in Gaza or the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Izzadin Kassam declared in a leaflet a
resumption of suicide bomb attacks against Israel in response to
the heavy crackdown on the organization by Israel and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The warning came as Israel is making last preparations for
Passover, one of the biggest Jewish holidays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
