<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-run Commerce Helps Curb Price Hikes in Anhui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The state-run commerce in Anhui
Province played an important role in bringing down price hikes by
10.6 percentage points in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The sufficient supplies of meat, vegetables, sugar, edible oil
and salt in the state sector helped keep the consumer price index
at 12.7 percent last year, down from 23.3 percent in the previous
year, and two percent lower than the national average.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the rise of prices of vegetables, meat, poultry, eggs
and egg products was over 20 percentage points lower, thanks to
the assistance of the state sector.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that state commerce still accounts for 65
percent and 95 percent of the sales of sugar and salt, and over 50
percent of household electronic goods and cultural products.
</P>
<P>
Last year the province opened five more large department stores
each exceeding 100 million yuan (12.04 million US dollars) in
retail sales, making the state commerce even stronger.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure supplies, the province has set up reserves
of pork and other major foodstuffs at both the provincial and city
levels. An extra 7,600 tons of pork was added last year, enabling
the state-run shops to sell the meat at 10-15 percent lower than
the market price during major festival periods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 07:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 25,000 TB Cases Reported In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- There are more than 25,000 people
suffering from tuberculosis (TB) in Zimbabwe, about three times
more than in previous years, the local "Herald Daily" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The TB officer at the Harare Central Hospital Jane Wingwsiri
said on Tuesday that everybody was at risk of contracting TB, an
air-borne disease which is now curable.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, anyone diagnosed as having the TB bacteria is
treated free at any health institutions.
</P>
<P>
"For as long as one complies with the treatment, TB is a very
curable disease," he said.
</P>
<P>
The officer also dismissed as untrue the common belief that TB
was linked to HIV.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone whether they are HIV positive or not are at risk of
contracting TB," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
