<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 07:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Maintains High Alert as Holiday Sets in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli security forces have
been put on increased alert for fear that the Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) should launch renewed suicide attacks during the
week-long Passover Holiday beginning tonight.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of policemen, border policemen, security agents,
Civil Guard volunteers and the army men are mobilized on duty
throughout the Passover, one of the most significant Jewish
holidays, to ensure that the rest of the population can celebrate
the festival safely. The police have urged the public to report
suspicious objects, individuals, or vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The police will also take extra steps to enforce traffic
regulations so as to prevent holiday-makers from begetting any
mishaps. Traffic accident is one of the major killers in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff, Lt.-Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, told the
Knesset (parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee Tuesday
that Israel has information that Hamas and Islamic Jihad still
intend to carry out attacks. He said that the closure of the Gaza
Strip is strict, but unlike Gaza, the closure of the West Bank is
"shaky" and it is easier for a lone attacker to cross the Green
Line from there.
</P>
<P>
As if to prove Shahak's warning, Hamas warned Tuesday that
it might resume suicide attacks against Israelis to punish the
Palestinian Authority for its campaign against Islamic
fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
A leaflet signed by its armed wing, Izzadin Kassam,
recommended what it called "lighting a fire again in the heart of
the Zionist state." 
</P>
