<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Uses 80 Percent of World Bank Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 3 (Xinhua)-- Sri Lanka's Ministry of Higher
Education and Education has used 80 percent of the funds made
available under the World Bank educational project, according to a
release from the ministry today.
</P>
<P>
The release said that the other 20 percent of the loan funds
will also be used by the end of this year under the supervision of
the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, referring Tuesday to a report about easy-term
loans made available under the World Bank educational project,
said that of the total loan of 65 million US dollars, 40 million
dollars has been used up to now.
</P>
<P>
The funds have been mainly used for school development,
building of laboratories, purchase of equipment and furniture
required for schools and human resources development, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the World Bank has been satisfied with the
performance of the project and another education development
project financed by easy-term loans from the World Bank is due to
be launched at the beginning of next year.  
