<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 07:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Sets Targets for Developing Social Security System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Beijing municipal government has
worked out plans to launch a series of reforms to improve its
social security system in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
These reforms will focus on developing social insurance,
old-age pension insurance, medicare and unemployment insurance,
Xinhua learned from the ongoing Fourth Session of the 10th Beijing
Municipal People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
As a result of these efforts, some 90 percent of urban and
township residents are expected to participate in social security
programs, and in rural areas the ratio is expected to exceed 50
percent by the year 2000. By the year 2010 all urban and rural
residents are expected to benefit from social security programs.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the local government plans to expand social
security programs from among workers in state enterprises and some
collective firms to all township workers and further expand them
among rural residents. Administrative organizations will be
established to monitor social security programs.
</P>
<P>
The local government will also devote efforts to effectively
raise and use social security funds to promote work in this
connection. Government, enterprises and individuals will share the
responsibility of raising and managing social security funds.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of 1995, 2.7 million people --
equal to 94 percent of the total number of workers in the
city-administered enterprises -- had participated in basic old-age
pension insurance. Eighty-seven percent, 2.21 million, of the
total number of enterprise workers had participated in insurance
on unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
