<HEADLINE> New Zealand Rejects US Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A New Zealand ban on Alaskan
salmon has been misrepresented in a United States report on trade
barriers, said NZ Trade Negotiations Minister Philip Burdon.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand was named in the report, released yesterday, as one
of the 40 countries which the report charged had erected "harmful
trade barriers" against US companies.
</P>
<P>
However, Burdon was quoted by a local press report today as
saying that the US Trade Representative's office had got some
facts wrong.
</P>
<P>
He said that a claim that a New Zealand prohibition on Alaskan
salmon breached World Trade Organization rules was
"comprehensively incorrect."
</P>
<P>
"They claim that New Zealand is breaching WTO rules. We are not
and no country has been more meticulous in honoring its WTO
commitments," Burdon stated.
</P>
<P>
He said New Zealand was still waiting to receive information
for a risk analysis of Alaskan salmon imports.
</P>
<P>
He said the Government regretted at the misrepresentation on
the question of salmon imports from Alaska, but welcomed a
description in the report of New Zealand's trade and investment
policy as the "bellwether for regional and global trade and
investment liberalization."  
</P>
</TEXT>
