<HEADLINE> Haikou Customs Cracks 334 Smuggling Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The customs in this capital of
China's island province of Hainan cracked 334 smuggling cases last
year, involving 230 million yuan-worth of goods.
</P>
<P>
It has been intensifying the fight against smugglers both on
the sea and at customs inspection posts to safeguard the economic
development of China's biggest special economic zone, a customs
officer said here today.
</P>
<P>
One million yuan-worth of goods were involved in 18 of the
cases, and 10 million yuan-worth of goods were involved in two
cases.
</P>
<P>
Most of the smuggled goods were cigarettes, steel products,
automobiles, motorcycles, oil products, building materials and
electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
To curb the rampant smuggling in the surrounding sea areas of
Hainan Island, the customs launched special patrols. Thirty-six
smuggling ships were seized this way.
</P>
<P>
The customs bureau has also strengthened efforts to counter
fake import deals. It found 103 such cases with 81 million yuan of
goods involved in 1995, and discovered 8.15 million yuan of
smuggled currencies at the same time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
