<HEADLINE> IMF Aid To Zimbabwe Remains Frozen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's largest bank said on
Tuesday there is little prospect of the country reaching
agreement with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on the
resumption of key balance-of-payments assistance until after July
this year.
</P>
<P>
"Despite official optimism, there is little prospect of an IMF
agreement until after the July budget, though IMF and other donor
disbursements could resume during the third quarter," the
Standard Chartered Bank Zimbabwe Ltd said in its latest economic
highlights.
</P>
<P>
The IMF last September suspended disbursement of over 63
million U.S. Dollars in balance-of-payments aid, citing serious
fiscal imbalances which it said could threaten macro-economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
Other donors, notably the World Bank, took similar actions.
</P>
<P>
Following the suspension of the aid, the IMF and the
Zimbabwean government agreed during bilateral talks held in
Washington on a programme of action aimed at winning back donor
support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
