<HEADLINE> Beijing Registers 1,111 Overseas Copyright Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital has registered
1,111 copyright contracts with foreign and Taiwan, Hong Kong and
Macao publishing houses in the past year.
</P>
<P>
According to Tuesday's "Beijing Evening News", the local
copyright administration required, as of February 1, 1995, all
publishing houses to register their copyright contracts once they
printed overseas publications.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 local publishing houses have registered 1,111 such
contracts when they decided to publish overseas books, of which 24
percent are on science and technology, computer science in
particular.
</P>
<P>
The local administration has also ordered the improvement of
the registration of overseas-related copyrights for computer
software, laser discs and compact discs.
</P>
<P>
Those who infringe or pirate copyrights will face
administrative or legal punishment.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 Chinese courts handled 400 copyright cases, an increase
of 20 percent over 1994. Of them, 70 percent were settled by legal
decision, 25 percent were mediated and the rest were dealt with by
other methods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
