<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Striving for Good Grain Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- More than eight million farmers in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region are hoping for
another good grain harvest this year.
</P>
<P>
"We have already had good grain harvests for 18 years running,
and are expecting the 19th good harvest year," said Liu Yanliang,
an agronomist with the regional bureau of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the regional government has allocated more
funds for agro-science, farm equipment and raw materials this year.
</P>
<P>
The region plans to grow crops on three million hectares this
year.
</P>
<P>
Included are 800,000 ha of cotton, up 66,700 ha over last year;
1.53 million ha of grain, the same as last year; and 100,000 ha of
beet, up 26,700 ha.
</P>
<P>
While sending officials and agro-scientists to rural areas to
help with farming, the regional government has supplied enough
chemical fertilizers, pesticides, plastic sheeting and farm
machinery on time, and granted more loans to farmers.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that the region turned out 925,000 tons of
cotton last year, ranking first in the country, and 7.3 million
tons of grain, making it self-sufficient in grain. The per capita
income of farmers last year topped 1,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
This year will see the region produce 1.02 million tons of
cotton and 7.4 million tons of grain, and the per capita income of
farmers will reach 1,250 yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
