<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 06:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mount Qilian Admitted into China Biosphere Protection Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Mount Qilian Nature Reserve in
northwest China has been admitted into the China biosphere
protection network, according to sources with the China State
Commission for Man and the Biosphere.
</P>
<P>
The largest forest and wild life protection area in inland
China, the reserve extends 1,200 km along the borders of Qinghai
and Gansu provinces. It was designated as a state nature reserve
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Since ancient times Mount Qilian has played a vital role in
protecting the biological balance, regulating water sources and
nurturing life varieties in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
A glacier over 5,000 m above sea level is the largest solid
reservoir in inland China, nourishing 56 tributaries flowing into
three water systems and irrigating large patches of farmland in
Qinghai and Gansu.
</P>
<P>
Forests on the mountain cover more than 2.6 million ha, the
largest area of forest reservation in inland China, and they play
a significant role in retaining water and preventing soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
The mountain also boasts abundant wild life, including snow
leopards, Asiatic wild asses and golden eagles.
</P>
<P>
The China biosphere protection network, established by the
China State Commission for Man and the Biosphere, is aimed at
contributing to the protection of and research into biological
varieties worldwide in accordance with an overall program of the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 06:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou Aims High in Developing Energy Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou province
is striving hard to develop energy resources and trying to become
a major energy producer in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
So far, the province has verified total coal deposits of 50.7
billion tons, the fifth-largest in the country. It still has a
potential power generating capacity of 16.84 million kw by taking
advantage of water resources, making it fourth in the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 the province developed a total power capacity of 4.34
million kw and turned out nearly 22.59 billion kwh of electricity,
with average annual increase hitting 12 percent and 16.8 percent,
respectively, over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the province produced 55.1 million tons of
coal, showing an average annual increase of 8.3 percent. It also
provided 10 million tons of coal and 2.7 billion kwh of
electricity to other provinces and regions.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the power industry, some 70 cities and
counties, or 81.4 percent of the total in Guizhou, have been
connected to the south China power grid.
</P>
<P>
To speed up the development of energy resources the province
has set the targets of producing 70 million tons of coal and
develop an installed power capacity of eight million kw annually
by the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
