<HEADLINE> Child Labor in Indonesia Draws World Bank's Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- An expert at the World Bank's
Jakarta office Tuesday urged the Indonesian government to
intervene in the exploitative child labor and poor working
conditions, especially for women, in the country.
</P>
<P>
The expert, Nisha Agrawal, made the call at a seminar here on
Indonesia's economic reforms and labor market restructuring.
</P>
<P>
According to a labor force survey of Indonesia, about two
million children aged between 10 and 14 are working voluntarily to
help their families make both ends meet.
</P>
<P>
Nisha said the number of child workers in the country was
declining thanks to a nine-year compulsory education program and
an economic growth in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
However, while the total number of child workers dropped by
about 26 percent from 1986 to 1994, the number of children working
in urban areas has doubled due to industrialization.
</P>
<P>
Nisha also urged the government to address the poor working
conditions for women, especially in the labor-intensive
manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
She criticized the nationwide malpractice for not providing
women workers with family and medical allowances, adding that
women workers are still subject to discrimination in the country.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
