<HEADLINE> Unknown Disease Claims 200 Lives in West Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- An outbreak of an unknown
epidemic has claimed more than 200 lives at villages in western
Nepal in the last two months, the Kathmandu Post said today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 218 people had died of the mysterious fever in the
hilly districts of Bajura, Jajarkot and Achham as local hospitals
failed to control the spread of the disease due to lack of
medicine and health workers, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The government has sent a team of doctors and other medical
help to the three affected districts, Director General of the
Health Department Kalyan Pandey said in an interview with the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"The disease broke out two months ago but we did not know about
it until it was very late," said Pandey.
</P>
<P>
People who are hit by the disease often die suddenly after
suffering apparently common symptoms like light fever, headache,
pain in the joints and loss of appetite, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Arjun Narsingh K. C. Tuesday inspected two
villages affected by the epidemic in Jajarkot and Achham
districts.  
</P>
