<HEADLINE> Cement Stock Gluts Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Cement companies in Vietnam are
searching for ways to dispose of their rising stock in the face of
sluggish market demand, an official report said today.
</P>
<P>
The stock in Ho Chi Minh City already reached 180,000 tons
while the reserve in Hanoi is still growing by an average of 500
to 1,000 tons per day.
</P>
<P>
Cement imports from China, South Korea and Thailand have
reached 280,000 tons, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The overstock came in the wake of last year's cement crisis
which was caused by a shortfall in supply and highly inflated
prices.
</P>
<P>
Though the Ministry of Construction estimated that the country
needs to stock 500,000 tons of cement this year, the estimate
backfired against cement companies as demand has been dropping
since late January and the pace of construction projects has
slowed down.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials, however, still predicted an annual demand
of 8.5 million tons for the year and expected a shortfall of 1.5
million tons.
</P>
<P>
The country has planned to build 19 large cement plants to cope
with an expected 20 percent annual increase in demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
