<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Indicators Surge in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Conflicting U.S. economic figures
today showed a sharp recovery in a key index of short-term
economic indicators, but lower than estimated growth in the
economy in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Index of Leading Economic Indicators, an important gauge of
future economic activity, made its sharpest monthly gain in 20
years in February, climbing 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the index's publishers, the private business research group
Confeence Board, said the rise was largely due to businesses
recovering from January's blizzards. And analysts said the rebound
doesn't signal a coming boom.
</P>
<P>
The government announced that economic growth in the
fourth quarter of 1995 was lower than previously estimated, at 0.5
percent rather than the forecast 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product (GDP) -- the total output of goods and
services in the United States -- grew just 2 percent last year,
the smallest annual advance since the economy shrank 1 percent
during a recession in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The monthly rise in the Index in February was the largest since
a 1.4 percent gain in January 1976. But economists view the index
as a true indication of the future only when it moves in the same
direction for three straight months or more.
</P>
<P>
So while the index rose 0.5 per cent to 101.5 in February, it
fell 0.5 percent in January to 100.2, against 100.7 in December.
The index is based on a 1987 benchmark of 100.
</P>
<P>
Of the index's 11 components, seven increased, including the
prices of materials, vendor deliveries, unfilled orders for
durable goods and building permits. Four indicators, including
consumer expectations and first-time claims for unemployment
declined.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department said its downward revision of fourth
quarter growth, despite strong consumer spending, was due to
sluggish capital spending by companies. The change, from 0.9 to
0.5 percent, was greater than the 0.8 percent analysts had
pencilled in.
</P>
<P>
For the year, the government revised its GDP
estimate down from 2.1 percent to two percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
