<HEADLINE> Teen Pregnancy Rate in US High in Early 1990s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Teenage pregnancy and abortion
rates in the United States were high in the early 1990s,
according to a report in Wednesday's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
The report said, statistics from 40 states show that the
pregnancy rate among the under-15 group was 6.3 per thousand in
1980, rising to 6.9 by 1985 and to 7.1 by 1990.
</P>
<P>
Among girls ages 15 to 19, it was 88.8 per thousand in
1980, dipping to 87.7 in 1985 and rising again to 95.9 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The federal government's goal was no births in the under-15 age
group by 1990. But in that year, 22,928 girls younger than 15
became pregnant, 11,657 gave birth and 11,271 had abortions, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
