<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 04:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Belarus Agree to Establish New Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Belarus today signed a
treaty of establishing the Community of Sovereign Republics in a
bid to speed up economic and political integration among the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony in the Kremlin, Russian President
Boris Yeltsin said the signing was a "historic moment," and called
the treaty a "document that opens a radically new stage in the
history of two sovereign peoples, two sovereign states."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who is seeking a second term as president in June
elections, hopes the treaty will attract voters nostalgic for the
Soviet Union while Belarus' President Alexander Lukashenko, who
arrived early today, wants Russia to help solve his country's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was also the culmination of Lukashenko's
two-year drive to bring his country of 10 million back into a
union of some kind with their 150 million Russian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"The dream of the peoples of the former Soviet Union to join
together, especially the Slavs, is starting to come true," said
Lukashenko at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, The Russian parliament hailed the signing of
the treaty, saying it will serve the integration of the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS)
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said the signing is
a first step in the process of closer integration, and hoped that
other CIS member states will join in the integration process.
</P>
<P>
The Russia-Belarus treaty said both had "decided on a voluntary
basis to form a deeply integrated political and economic Community
of Sovereign Republics".
</P>
<P>
Other economic clauses of the treaty envisage synchronized
moves by the end of 1997 to create a common market with free
movement of goods, services, capital and labor.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, a council, with Lukashenko as its chairman,
will govern the community.
</P>
<P>
The council is made up of the two countries' presidents, prime
ministers and parliament leaders.
</P>
<P>
The creation of the new union came just two weeks after the
Russian State Duma passed a resolution declaring the breakup of
the Soviet Union in 1991 illegal and demanding its restoration.
</P>
<P>
Call and Support for deepening ties between former Soviet Union
republics have been growing, especially in Belarus, Kazakhstan and
Kyrgyzstan, whose economic reforms have been in trouble without
subsidies and cheap energy from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Last Week, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Belarus signed a
an agreement pledging to expand links among themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 04:25 </DATE_TIME>
