<HEADLINE> China's Hi-tech Research to Focus on Five Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China's "Program 863", a long-term
high technology research and development program, will focus on
the five key fields of biology, information, automation, energy
and new materials during 1996-2000 period, today's "China Daily"
reports.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an ongoing meeting on the program, Zhu Lilan,
vice-minister of the State Science and Technology Commission, said
the project will give a powerful push to the modernization drive,
especially in agriculture and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Research in these areas will be exploited commercially, she
added.
</P>
<P>
The official added that through gene transplants, the country
will expand experimental growing of hybrid rice, and pest- and
disease-resistant cotton, wheat, maize and soybeans.
</P>
<P>
The commission will also focus on gene injection technology
research to improve treatment of malignant tumors, and a clinical
trial of gene medicine vaccines for hepatitis, intestinal disease,
snail fever and malaria.
</P>
<P>
The information field will target high performance computers,
optics and electronics, air-to-surface and surface-to-air
observation, and modern telecommunications, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
In the next five years, computerized manufacturing systems are
expected to be further utilized in such areas as machinery,
electronics, space, textiles, light industry, petroleum, chemistry
and telecommunications. Industrial robots will also be used in
some large firms.
</P>
<P>
The materials field will cover materials used in electronics,
information, rare earth, new energy, compound materials and
high-capacity engineering plastics.
</P>
<P>
The "Project 863" launched in march 1986 is a 15 year plan
designed to provide advanced science and technology for the
national economy and defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
