<HEADLINE> China Releases White Paper on Situation of Its Children (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I. Guarantee of Children's Rights and Interests
</P>
<P>
Children are the future and hope of mankind. Today's children
will be masters of the 21st century. Children's survival,
protection and development, which are the basis for improving the
quality of the population and the prerequisite conditions for the
advance of mankind, directly concern a country and a nation's
future and destiny. The Chinese nation has long cultivated the
traditional virtues of "bringing along the young" and "loving
the young." An old saying, "Love our own and others' children,"
is still very popular. The Chinese Government, with an earnest and
responsible attitude, always shows great concern for children's
survival, protection and development. It regards "the education
of children to improve the quality of the whole people" as a
fundamental policy for its socialist modernization program. The
government educates society at large to "protect and educate
children, and set an example and do practical things for
children." It spares no effort to create favorable social
conditions for the progress of children's programs. Since the
initiation of reform and opening to the outside world, children's
programs in China have moved into social, scientific and legal
tracks; and children's programs have become an important component
part of the nation's construction and the duties of the whole
society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 04:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Paper on Situation of Children in China Issued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A white paper on the situation of
children in China released today by the Information Office of the
State Council fully introduces to the world, with a host of facts
and accurate statistics, the unremitting efforts China has made
made and the achievements it has scored in children's survival,
protection and development, refuting the slandering and
accusations about the situation of children in China by some
foreign media and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
The paper on "The Situation of Children in China" consists of
five parts: "Guarantee of Children's Rights and Interests",
"Children's Health and Care", "Education for Children",
"Protection of Disabled Children", and "China's Welfare Homes for
Children", totalling 15,000 Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
The paper says, China has a population of over 1.2 billion, of
whom over 300 million are children under the age of 16, making up
about one fifth of the total number of children in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government, with an earnest and responsible
attitude, always shows great concern for children's survival,
protection and development. Since the initiation of reform and
opening to the outside world, children's programs in China have
moved into social, scientific and legal tracks, and children's
programs have become an important component part of the nation's
construction and the duties of the whole society, the paper notes.
</P>
<P>
The paper continues, the Chinese government has done a great
deal of painstaking work in protecting children's lives and
health. As a result, remarkable success has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the 1990s, the annual rate of decrease
of infant mortality in China is 6.5 percent and that of children
under five years old is 5.85 percent. The paper points out that so
far, no other country in the world enjoying an annual per capita
income approximate to China has reached such a high level.
</P>
<P>
It says, the Chinese government always gives pride of place to
children's education in the promotion of education in general. In
1995, the enrollment ratio of school-age children in primary
schools was 98.5 percent, the enrollment ratio of school-age girls
was 98.2 percent, and 90.8 percent of primary school graduates
entered a higher school.
</P>
<P>
The paper stresses, China has all along attached importance to
protecting disabled children, making great efforts to create
favorable conditions for their survival and development.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, China had rectified 360,000 children of
polio sequelae, a success rate of 98 percent; helped more than
60,000 deaf children recover their hearing and speech abilities,
provided 30,000 poor-sighted children with sight aids and helped
100,000 mentally retarded children enhence their cognitive ability
and ability of taking care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
The paper gives detailed introduction of China's welfare homes
for children. It says, by the end of 1995, there were a total of
73 welfare homes for children set up by local governments, taking
care of 8,900 orphans and abandoned ill or disabled children. More
than 1,200 social welfare institutions and some homes for the aged
in rural areas have also offered guardianship and rearing to
orphans and abandoned ill or disabled children.
</P>
<P>
The paper says, currently, there are about 20,000 such children
under the guardianship and rearing of welfare institutions,
accounting for five per one hundred thousand of the total number
of juveniles in China.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the Chinese government appropriated 740
million yuan specially for the improvement of welfare homes for
children. These funds have guaranteed the basic needs of the
children's lives in the welfare homes.
</P>
<P>
The paper points out, China has made great efforts to support
the survival, protection and development of children. the UNICEF,
UNESCO, WHO and other international organizations and public
figures all made positive comments on China's achievements in this
connection.
</P>
<P>
Of course, the paper says, the Chinese government is sober
about the fact that since China is a developing country with a
large population and since its economic foundation is still
comparatively weak, its per capita income is in a rather rear
position in the world per capita income listings and its
development level is unbalanced between city and countryside and
between different areas, there is much difficulty in the work for
children and therefore much room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
The paper notes, therefore, as China develops economically and
socially, an important task facing the Chinese government is to
constantly improve children's conditions and promote activities
and programs to help children.
</P>
<P>
The paper also refutes strongly in the appendix the slandering
and accusations about China's children's welfare institutions by
Britain's commercial television station Channel Four and Human
Rights Watch/Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
