<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 04:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Achievements in Reducing Infant Mortality Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The annual rate of decrease of
infant mortality in China since 1990 is 6.5 percent and that of
children under five years old is 5.85 percent. So far, no other
country in the world enjoying an annual per capita income
approximate to China's has reached such a high level, according to
the white paper on the situation of Chinese children issued by the
Information Office of the State Council here today.
</P>
<P>
Since the implementation of China's immunization program at the
end of the 1970s, great achievements have been made and the
incidence of infectious diseases has sharply declined, the white
paper says. A national report on the country's epidemic situation
reveals that the number of cases of measles, diphtheria, pertussis
and poliomyelitis in 1994 dropped by 96.4, 99.4, 99.3 and 97.5
percent respectively compared with 1978; the death rate decreased
by 97.4, 99.3, 96.5 and 97.7 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The white paper notes that China considers reducing children's
mortality caused by pneumonia and diarrhoea as an important and
urgent task of its medical and health work for children. For this
purpose a series of measures, such as popularizing proper
techniques, personnel training, health education and monitoring
systems have been adopted to reduce infant mortality, especially
rural infant mortality. In order to eliminate infant mortality
caused by tetanus, China, while continuing to popularize the new
methods of child delivery and encourage hospital childbirths, has
striven to rapidly develop immunization work among women of
childbearing age.
</P>
<P>
According to the white paper, China has paid great attention to
improving children's nutritional status and adopted various
medical and health measures.
</P>
<P>
In the early period after the founding of the People's Republic
of China the government handed out infant food in some areas. In
the 1960s and 1970s a scientific diet for children was popularized
in China. the supplementary food was developed in the 1980s and
breast feeding was advocated and dietary scheme was optimized in
the 1990s, having greatly improved the nutritional status of
Chinese children. Now it is rare to find cases of serious
malnutrition caused by shortage of food or cases of serious
vitamin-A deficiency. By the end of 1995, 2,957 baby friendly
hospitals had been constructed, ranking first in number in the
world.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, in order to improve the level of medical
treatment and health care and the nutritional status of children
in rural areas, measures for promoting the building of township
clinics, county health and antiepidemic stations, and county
health centers for women and children have been adopted by the
state, the white paper says. Compared with 1990, the rate of
malnutrition in children under five years old had dropped by 23.82
percent in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 04:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Releases White Paper on Situation of Its Children (18) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese Government has expended great efforts and attained
remarkable achievements in helping disabled children recover
maximum health and in enhancing their abilities to participate in
social life.
</P>
<P>
China has actively developed the "Three Recoveries" program
(rectifying polio sequelae, training deaf children in hearing and
speech and performing cataract operations). By the end of 1995,
China had rectified 360,000 children of polio sequelae (a success
rate of 98 percent), helped more than 60,000 deaf children recover
their hearing and speech abilities (10 percent of which had
entered regular kindergartens and elementary schools to receive
regular education), had provided 30,000 poor-sighted children with
sight aids and helped 100,000 mentally retarded children enhance
their cognitive capacity and self-sufficiency. At present, China
has established the National Rehabilitation Research Center for
Deaf Children, in addition to 26 provincial-level rehabilitation
centers for deaf children and over 1,000 rehabilitation stations,
kindergartens and training classes for disabled children.
</P>
<P>
Community rehabilitation service systems for disabled children
also have been set up. China has fully used the urban-rural
three-level network of health services to develop community
rehabilitation, helping most disabled children in grassroots areas
enjoy basic rehabilitation services. Moreover, under the
leadership of local governments at different levels, community
rehabilitation leading groups have been founded, consisting of
public health departments, civil administration departments,
disabled persons' federations and other relevant departments,
which coordinate and cooperate with each other to mutually
formulate community rehabilitation plans and manage their
implementation.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, the Chinese Ministry of Civil Affairs started to
cooperate with the UNICEF in the Community Rehabilitation for
Disabled Children project. By the end of 1994, the rehabilitation
network for disabled children covered 32 cities and counties in 23
provinces of the country and systematically trained disabled
children's parents and rehabilitation instructors. These efforts
were successful in effectively improving the management of the
rehabilitation work for disabled children.
</P>
</TEXT>
