<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 03:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes Good Care of Disabled Children: White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China has all along attached
importance to protecting disabled children, making great efforts
to create favorable conditions for their survival and
development, according to the White Paper on "The Situation of
Children in China", which was issued by the Information office of
the State Council here today.
</P>
<P>
The White Paper says that the Chinese government has expended
great efforts to prevent congenital disability by adopting a
series of measures, such as a comprehensive immunization program
and supplying iodized salt. Meanwhile, the country has actively
developed the "Three Recoveries" program (rectifying polio
sequelae, training deaf or dumb children to hear or speak and
performing cataract operations). By the end of 1995 China had
rectified polio sequelae in 360,000 children (a success rate of 98
percent), helped more than 60,000 deaf or dumb children recover
their hearing or speech abilities (10 percent of them have since
entered regular kindergartens and elementary schools), provided
30,000 poor-sighted children with sight aids, and helped 100,000
mentaly retarded children enhance their cognitive capacity and
self-sufficiency. In addition, it has established the National
Rehabilitation Research Center for Deaf Children, in addition to
26 provincial-level rehabilitation centers for deaf children and
over 1,000 rehabilitation stations, kindergartens and training
classes for disabled children.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that after years of efforts China has formed a
compulsory education set-up for disabled children, with
special-education schools as well as special-education classes
attached to ordinary schools. By the end of 1995 China had set up
1,379 special-education schools for blind, deaf and mentally
retarded children, an increase of 400 percent over 1980. There
were also 6,510 special-education classes attached to
ordinary schools, with 296,000 disabled students (including those
attending regular schools), an increase of 800 percent over
1980. In addition, in 1995 the national average school enrollment
rate of blind, deaf and mentally retarded children reached 60
percent; in the economically developed areas enrollment reached
80 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese government has done a great deal of
work to mobilize various circles in society to care for, in
various ways, disabled children, to encourage the spirit of
self-improvement among disabled children and to advocate the
social virtues of unity, friendship and mutual aid. The Chinese
media actively reports on the lives of disabled children and the
work concerning the disabled. As a result, the broad masses of
people all over the country also widely participate in various
activities to help the disabled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 03:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Releases White Paper on Situation of Its Children (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In order to eliminate poliomyelitis, while strengthening
regular work on immunity and the monitoring of poliomyelitis,
China performed nationwide six rounds of reinforced inoculations
on children under four years old, on December 5 and January 5
separately in each of the three years 1993-96, each round
involving about 80 million children. In this way the timetable
for eliminating poliomyelitis has been shortened.
</P>
<P>
Since the implementation of China's immunization program, great
achievements have been made and the incidence of infectious
diseases has sharply declined. A national report on the country's
epidemic situation reveals that the number of cases of measles,
diphtheria, pertussis and poliomyelitis in 1994 dropped by 96.4,
99.4, 99.3 and 97.5 percent respectively compared with 1978; the
death rate decreased by 97.4, 99.3, 96.5 and 97.7 percent
respectively. In 1994, the number of incidences of the
above-mentioned four epidemic diseases fell by about 3.517 million
and the number of deaths by about 13,000 as compared with 1978. In
1995, only one strain of a wild virus was found in the stool of a
child suffering from poliomyelitis who came from abroad to Yunnan
for medical treatment. No other poliomyelitis wild viruses were
found in Acute Flaccid Paralise cases.
</P>
<P>
China's immunization achievements have been highly praised by
the international community. On October 16, 1989, a silver medal
was awarded to the Chinese Health and Antiepidemic Department of
the Ministry of Public Health by the then UNICEF executive
director, James P. Grant to commend China's achievements made in
children's immunity work. On November 24, 1994 and August 8, 1995,
Dr Hiroshi Nakajima, Director General of the WHO and Dr S. T. Han,
Director of Western Pacific Regional Office of the WHO,
successively wrote letters to Li Peng, Premier of the State
Council of the People's Republic of China, and Qiao Shi, Chairman
of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, in
which they spoke highly of these achievements and, on behalf of
the WHO, expressed their great satisfaction with China's work in
eliminating poliomyelitis. They held that China had played an
important role in the world public health field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
