<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 03:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Shows Concern for Children's Rights: White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A white paper issued by China says
that the Chinese government, with an earnest and responsible
attitude, has always shown great concern and attached great
importance to children's rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, titled "The situation of Children in China",
was released here today by the Information Office of the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
The paper says there are over 300 million children under the
age of 16 among China's population of over 1.2 billion, making up
about one fifth of the total number of children in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government, with an earnest and responsible
attitude, always shows great concern for children's survival,
protection and development, it stresses.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 the Chinese government formally promulgated the
Outline of the Program for Chinese Children's Development in the
1990s, which puts forward ten main objectives and measures for
realizing these objectives.
</P>
<P>
The paper goes on to say that the constitution of China
clearly specifies that "... children are protected by the state"
and "maltreatment of ...children is prohibited".
</P>
<P>
Formulated according to the constitution, China's relevant
laws include comprehensive and systematic provisions on children's
right to life, survival and development, as well as basic health
and health care. The provisions also address children's family
environment and institutional care, education, free time and
cultural activities, and the special protection of disabled
children.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China's constitution, laws and relevant
administrative legislation also include comparatively complete
provisions on the government's functions, society's participation,
work principles and corresponding legal responsibilities in the
protection of children's rights and interests. The judicial
procedure attaches great importance to the protection of
juveniles' legal rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
The paper concludes that China's legal framework for the
protection of children's interests and its social guarantee
mechanisms are effective in practice.
</P>
<P>
To truly protect children's rights and interests, China's
legislation, and judicial and government departments concerned as
well as mass organizations have set up corresponding mechanisms
to supervise, effect and propel the healthy development of work
impacting children's protection, it adds.
</P>
<P>
China has taken an active part in global and regional
co-operation and exchanges regarding children's survival,
protection and development, actively participated in working out
the UN Convention on the Rights of Children, and was one of the
co-sponsor countries that raised the draft resolution for the
approval of the convention, the paper says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
