<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 03:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Priority Given to Children's Education: White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Children's education always claims
precedence in China's educational development, and 98.5 percent of
all school-age children across the country were at school in 1995,
the Information Office of the State Council stated in a white
paper issued here today.
</P>
<P>
"The Situation of Children in China", as the white paper is
named, said that the Chinese government always gives pride of
place to children's education in the promotion of education in
general. In 1994 China spent 59.4 billion yuan on primary
education, with operating expenses for public use averaging 89.47
yuan per student; 43.5 billion yuan was spent on ordinary middle
schools, with operating expenses for public use averaging 239.89
yuan per student.
</P>
<P>
China has been making great efforts to raise educational funds
through various channels. During 1991-1994 it collected a total of
33.8 billion yuan for primary and middle schools to buy more and
better quality teaching aids, books and reference materials,
sports requisites and campus facilities.
</P>
<P>
The white paper says that popularization of compulsory
nine-year schooling is the key goal of China's elementary
education program. In 1995 the number of children attending
primary schools reached 131.95 million, with an enrollment rate of
98.5 percent of children of school age. In 1995 the enrollment
ratio of school-age girls in primary schools was 98.2 percent. And
90.8 percent of the primary school graduates entered higher
schools. According to China's present standard on popularization
of compulsory primary schooling, elementary education has been
basically popularized in an area covering 91 percent of the
country's population.
</P>
<P>
The white paper says that UNESCO statistics show that the
enrollment ratio of school-age children in China is much higher
than in other countries of the same economic development level.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the concern of and vigorous promotion by the
government, people from all walks of life have been helping
drop-out children from poverty-stricken areas to return to school.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995 the Hope Project, which provides
grants-in-aid as long-term financial assistance to children in
poor areas who have dropped out of school because of straitened
family circumstances, had raised 690 million yuan, given financial
assistance to 1.25 million children for continuing primary
education and subsidized construction of over 2,000 Hope Project
primary schools. The Spring Buds Program, providing a special fund
to help girls in poor areas to receive charge-free compulsory
primary education, helped 100,000 girls return to school in 1994
and 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
