<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 03:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Welfare Homes Look After 20,000 Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- There are around 20,000 children,
or five for every 100,000 of the total number of juveniles in
China, who are being taken care of in various kinds of welfare
homes, according to the white paper on "The Situation of Children
in China", issued here today by the Information Office of the
State Council.
</P>
<P>
The white paper notes that welfare homes for children in China
play a special role in the country's efforts to care for children.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995 there were a total of 73 welfare homes for
children set up by local governments, taking care of 8,900 orphans
and abandoned disabled children. More than 1,200 social welfare
institutions and homes for the aged in rural areas have also
taken in orphans and abandoned disabled children. Currently, there
are around 20,000 children in the care of welfare institutions,
accounting for five per one hundred thousand of the total number
of juveniles in China.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, most of the funds for China's welfare
homes for children come from appropriations by state and local
financial departments, collective fund raising, welfare lotteries
and donations.
</P>
<P>
From 1990 to 1994 local financial departments had appropriated
a total of 515 million yuan directly for urban welfare homes for
children. Of this total, 40 percent was used for the basic needs
of the children, increasing by 25.5 percent annually. During this
period the state appropriated 740 million yuan specially for the
improvement of the welfare homes for children. All these funds
have ensured the basic needs for children's lives in the welfare
homes.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the welfare homes for children in China
practise the principle of combining upbringing, treatment and
education.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 the number of sick or disabled children in these homes
nursed back to health reached 200, and a total of 40 percent of
children in the welfare homes taking part in rehabilitation
training programs, and many of them have recovered or basically
recovered from disability. Welfare homes for children boast
doctors, rehabilitators, nutritionists, as well as clinics,
rehabilitation rooms, emergency treatment rooms, laboratories and
pharmacies, giving timely treatment to ailing children.
</P>
<P>
In welfare homes normal children receive compulsory education,
while the blind, deaf and mentally retarded children are educated
in special schools at the welfare homes' expense. Many children
have been brought up at the welfare homes. At present, China has
a contingent of professional staff who are devoted to the
well-being of orphans and disabled children; medical personnel
account for 32 percent of the total welfare home staff.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, mass movements to help orphans have
blossomed. many urban families take children from children's
welfare institutions and let them stay in their homes during
holidays or at ordinary times so that these children can enjoy the
warmth and affection of a family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
