<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inland Province To Expand Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou Province
targets its annual tourism revenue at 100 million US dollars and
three billion yuan by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The province's tourism income will then account for six percent
of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
It plans to receive a total of 100 million domestic and
overseas tourists over the next five years, with revenues reaching
320 million US dollars and 8.82 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou has developed two major travel routes, with the western
one featuring its karst scenery and the eastern one its folk
customs.
</P>
<P>
In the next five years it will focus on developing four
trans-provincial routes from this provincial capital to Kunming,
Zhangjiajie, Chongqing and Liuzhou, all major tourist spots in
neighboring Yunnan, Hunan, Sichuan provinces and the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The Guiyang-Kunming route is regarded as highly competitive
among China's newly developed travel routes.
</P>
<P>
Winding through western Guizhou to Kunming, a popular
destination for travelers from Southeast Asia, it takes in most of
Guizhou's karst scenery, including China's biggest waterfall,
Asia's biggest cave and a canyon.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 a total of 136,000 overseas and 17.5 million domestic
tourists arrived in the province, increases of 13 percent and 3.14
percent, respectively, over the previous year, and tourism
revenues reached 960 million yuan, according to the provincial
tourism bureau.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou has built 38 hotels catering to overseas
travelers. These hotels are able to receive 150,000 visitors a
year, a number which will be doubled by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a new airport is being constructed here, which is
scheduled to be put into operation in the summer of 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
