<HEADLINE> CIS Foreign Ministers Meet to Prepare for Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers from the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) met here today to prepare
for the upcoming CIS summit in May.
</P>
<P>
The ministers focused on discussing the 1996-1997 draft plan on
the CIS intergration, the implementation of the CIS Collective
Security Treaty and the Abkhazian question.
</P>
<P>
They also exchanged views on maintaining European security,
enhancing international cooperation and other issues.
</P>
<P>
On the Abkhazian question, the ministers failed to reach
consensus on the proposal put forward by Georgia on changing the
functions of the CIS peacekeeping forces stationed on its
territory.
</P>
<P>
A CIS military coordinator said Georgia demanded that the
peacekeeping forces be given a police role, and the question be
settled only through consultations between Georgia and Russia,
although the U.N. requests through tripartite negotiations by
Georgia, Russia and Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
Georgia and Abkhazia signed in Moscow in May 1994 an agreement
on ceasefire and the deployment of the CIS peacekeeping forces in
Abkhazia. The tenure of the CIS peacekeepers was renewed for
another year in May 1995.
</P>
<P>
The CIS official said if no agreement is reached until June
when the tenure of the peacekeeping forces expires, there will be
a danger of the renewal of conflicts in Abkhazia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
