<HEADLINE> Sydney 2000 Olympics to Surpass 390m Dollars Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Sydney 2000 Olympic Games
organisers expressed confident that they will easily surpass their
390 million U.S. dollars sponsorship target after receiving
the support of a large international corporation on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The prediction came after the Sydney Organising Committee for
the Olympic Games (Socog) announced they had signed a record deal
with Coca-Cola giving the company exclusive soft drinks rights for
the 2000 Olympics and associated promotions in the four years
leading to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said it is estimated to be worth more
than 37.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The soft drinks company is the third major corporation to sign
a sponsorship agreement with the Socog. The others are Australian
communications company Telstra and IBM.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola vice-president Stuart Cross Wednesday said: "Sydney
2000 will be the biggest, most supported program in the history of
the company behind the Olympic movement."
</P>
<P>
Socog chief executive Mal Hemmerling said Socog was ahead of
schedule of its target to raise more than 390 million U.S. dollars
in national corporate partnerships and licensing agreements
towards the 1.56 billion U.S. dollars Olympic budget.
</P>
<P>
He said that bigger than expected returns from the marketing
wing of the Socog, along with large profits from TV rights, have
heightened expectations of a bumper profit for the Sydney 2000
Olympics. 
</P>
