<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 03:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G7 Says Reforms Needed to Cut Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth, reforming labor
markets and curbing public deficits are crucial to cut worsening
unemployment, The Group of Seven leading industrial nations said
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A final statement, released by the two-day G7 conference of
labor and economics ministers in Lille, France, said the pressing
task was to make structural reforms in the labor market to make
it less rigid and more flexible to keep up with global trade
liberalization and the fast development of new technology.
</P>
<P>
Globalization and the development of information technology
breathe life into the world economy, but at the same time pose a
threat to labor markets, said the final statement.
</P>
<P>
The G7 nations -- the U.S., Canada, Britain, Italy, Germany,
Japan and France -- noted that small businesses could play a
bigger role in job creation so that they deserved more funds and
technological support from governments.
</P>
<P>
But vigorous growth could only be achieved with healthy public
finances, so G7 countries should try to control public spending
more effectively, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The G7 meeting was called by French President Jacques Chirac
to find ways to help beat unemployment which stands at some 22
million in the seven countries. Although unemployment in the
U.S. is around 5.5 percent, the average jobless rate in Europe is
11 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
