<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 03:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Monetary Institute Calls For Rectifying EU Finances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Monetary Institute today
called for the European Union (EU) nations to rectify their domestic
finances for a smooth entry into the European Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt-based institute, destined to be the central bank
of the entire future Europe, said given EU's current economic
situation, there is an urgent need for financial rectification.
</P>
<P>
Immediate actions are key to the success of the efforts in this
regard, the institute asserted in its annual report.
</P>
<P>
Alexandre Lamfalussy, president of the institute, said EMU's
timetable starting from early 1999 could be followed only with
appropriate economic policies, unified common standards, and
satisfactory economic developments.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, his institute hoped that EU member nations
could start early the financial rectification.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the 1995 performance, Lamfalussy said EU made great
progress in curbing inflation.
</P>
<P>
According to the annual report, EU nations' inflation averaged
3 percent in 1995, the same as the previous year. However,
Belgium, Denmark, Germany, France, Ireland, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Austria and Finland successfully managed to keep the
rate under annual 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lamfalussy noted, most EU nations still had budgetary
deficits substantially higher than 3 percent of their gross
domestic product (GDP) -- a limit set forth by the Maastricht
Treaty for further integrating Europe.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the total volume of state debt in many EU
nations were over 60 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The finance of public sectors is the weak point for keeping up
with the unified common monetary standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
