<HEADLINE> Romania Ends Second Phase of Privatization Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 12.4 million
security-holding Romanians have registered with nearly 4,000
state-owned enterprises, ending the government's second phase of
privatization program.
</P>
<P>
They account for 74.8 percent of the nation's security-holders,
Vice Prime Minister Mircea Cosea, who is in charge of the
implementation of the privatization program, said in a radio
broadcast today.
</P>
<P>
He said that those who don't want to register with state-owned
companies can go with four private capital funds by the end
of April.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the three-phased privatization program,
approved by the parliament in June 1995, demanded that
security-holders register with state or private companies.
</P>
<P>
During the first phase, the government issued privatization
securities to citizens free of charge.
</P>
<P>
And in the third phase, the state companies will turn the
securities into stocks which will then be returned to the same
security-holders.
</P>
<P>
After the completion of the second phase, the government will
issue stock-holding certificates to its citizens and to form a
capital market in the country, Cosea added.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts say the capital market will not be formed
until the completion of the privatization program, although
Romania set up a stock exchange last fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
