<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dudayev: Russian Troops Must Withdraw Before Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Chechen separatist leader Dzhokhar
Dudayev today said he was ready to negotiate with Moscow but only
after Russian troops had pulled out from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"Real negotiations can only take place once military operations
have been halted and after Russian troops have withdrawn from the
Chechen republic," Dudayev told the Azerbaijani news agency Turan,
in his first public response to Russian President Boris Yeltsin's
peace plan for the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
But the rebel leader doubted the sincerity of the offer and
said Yeltsin's conciliatory attitude was only a tactic for his
presidential reelection campaign.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin announced his long-awaited peace plan for war-torn
Chechnya on Sunday. He ordered a halt to combat operations,
promised a step by step troop withdrawal and free elections ahead
of negotiations on Chechnya's future status within the Russian
federation.
</P>
<P>
The president also said he is ready to hold peace talks with
Dudayev through intermediaries, something he had previously ruled
out.
</P>
<P>
But Yeltsin is under pressure to solve the 15-month crisis in
Chechnya, which has become a major obstacle in his path to
reelection in June. He faces a tough challenge from Communist
Party leader Gennady Zyuganov, who is ahead in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
Dudayev said, "The authorities in Moscow are not ready for any
normal talks," and they "have no desire at all to end the
conflict."
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he listed several possible intermediaries for the
peace talks, such as former Soviet president Mikhail Gorbachev,
president of Russia's republic of Tartarstan Mintimer Shaimiyev,
and leader of the Yabloko movement Grigory Yavlinsky, all of whom
he said have made efforts to mediate in the war.
</P>
<P>
Despite Yeltsin's pledge to halt military operations from
midnight Sunday night, he said, "there has been no ceasefire so
far," adding that the war would last until a new Russian president
is in power.
</P>
<P>
Fierce fighting raged between Russian forces and Dudayev's
guerrillas in southern Chechnya on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But in Grozny, the capital of the Caucasian republic, life
seems to be returning to a semblance of normality, with more
people and more vehicles appearing on the streets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
