<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Unveils European Defense Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Herve de
Charette said today that Europe should be bolstered by a strong
and united EU, a reformed and well-balanced NATO, and an enlarged
security alliance including Russia.
</P>
<P>
These three bodies should form the three pillars of European
defense, de Charette told a defense institute in Paris.
</P>
<P>
He also said the European Union should adopt common foreign and
defense policies and merge with the Western European Union (WEU),
Europe's only military alliance, made up of 10 of the EU's 15
members.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that a reformed NATO will enable European
countries to take military action when necessary. And within a
well-balanced NATO, Europe and the U.S. can conduct true political
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
France isn't a member of NATO but has been active in advocating
NATO reforms, supporting the maintenance of U.S. forces in Europe
while strengthening Europe's own forces, unified or independent.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also said Russia must be included in any
expanded defense organization. Without it, such an organization
would not be a real one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
