<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Million American Children Abused or Neglected: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- State agencies say 1 million
children are abused or neglected, with parents responsible for 80
percent of the damage.
</P>
<P>
Federal officials say the real toll may be three times as high,
because in many cases mistreatment is never substantiated and
reported by the states.
</P>
<P>
The National Center on Child Abuse and Neglect of the U.S.
Health and Human Service Department released a report Monday,
based on 1994 statistics collected from 47 states and the District
of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-three percent of the children suffered neglect.
Twenty-six percent were physically abused, 14 percent were
sexually abused, 5 percent were abused emotionally, and 22 percent
suffered other types of mistreatment, the Center said.
</P>
<P>
Substantiated cases of abuse or neglect increased 27 percent
during the five-year period beginning in 1990, officials said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been an increase in child abuse and neglect since
1990 which is attributed in part to drug use and an increase in
drugs that are highly addictive and cause severe behavioral
chances, such as crack cocaine," said Michael Kharfen, a spokesman
for the Health and Human Services Department (HHS).
</P>
<P>
Other studies indicate the actual number of abused and
neglected children may be much higher than the number the states
were able to substantiate, said Mary Jo Bane, HHS assistant
secretary for children and families.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results of a study ordered by Congress found 2.9
million children abused or mistreated in 1993. The National
Incidence Study of Child Abuse and Neglect receives information
from private professionals who have contacts with abused children,
in addition to state officials.
</P>
<P>
Forty-three states reported deaths from neglect or abuse,
totaling 1,111 child fatalities in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0302 </DOCNO>
