<HEADLINE> Thailand, Croatia Seek Stronger Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Croatia have agreed
to seek ways to forge closer economic and diplomatic ties, local
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are studying the possibility of concluding a
package of agreements to expand bilateral economic cooperation,
said visiting Croatian Deputy Prime Minister Mate Granic.
</P>
<P>
It is an appropriate time for cooperation on economic issues
between Thailand and Croatia, said Granic, who is also Croatia's
foreign minister, during a meeting with his Thai counterpart
Kasem. S. Kasemsri on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cranic arrived in Thailand on a five-day official visit after
his tours to Malaysia and Indonesia. He is scheduled to leave
Thailand later today.
</P>
<P>
Cranic also expressed hopes that there would be exchanges of
visits by businessmen and government officials between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Kasem said that he would encourage Thai businessmen to visit
Croatia, stressing that Thailand could use Croatian ports to
transport goods to Central European countries.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral diplomatic ties, Kasem said that the two
countries are to appoint honorary consuls in each other's capital.
He also expressed confidence that Thailand and Croatia would open
embassies in each other's capital when their relations are further
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was the first member of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations to recognize Croatia's independence in 1992.
Bilateral trade has been limited due to the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Thai embassy in Hungary oversees Croatia and the
Croatian embassy in Jakarta, Indonesia, oversees Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
