<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Get More Museums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China's capital city is to build a
group of museums centering on different specific topics in the
next five years, according to a local government decision.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the ratio of the number of museums to the total
local population is expected to reach 1:100,000. The number of
visitors to the museums is expected to exceed 50 million annually.
</P>
<P>
Beijing now has more than 120 museums, and some 90 of them have
been opened to the public. Each year these museums hold more than
400 exhibitions, attracting over 40 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has established special education
sections for young people in some 40 museums since 1992. More than
three million youngsters visit them annually.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the municipal government has launched a campaign to
strengthen the centralized management of museums established by
different departments in different areas, with certifications
having been given to 55 museums so far.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuchma Urges to Keep on Reforms in Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma today pledged to forge ahead with market reforms and fight
budget deficit and inflation to bail his country out of its
economic dilemma.
</P>
<P>
In his annual state-of-the-nation address to the parliament,
Kuchma said that 1995 will be remembered as Ukraine's most
successful year despite various social problems.
</P>
<P>
A lot was achieved politically and economically in the past
year, the president told the deputies, including the signing of
the constitutional accord which has paved the way for the
establishment of a constitutional government. Inflation rate
dropped from 72 percent in November 1994 to 4.6 percent in
December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said that Ukraine won recognition and affirmation from
the international community by joining the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
But the progress had to be made at the expense of the
Ukrainians whose living standard suffered from a downward economic
spiral.
</P>
<P>
He, however, rated 1996 as an important year in which the
country is to march out of its economic mire by stabilizing
macroeconomy and promoting privatization.
</P>
<P>
He said that the state will carry out reforms in the taxation
system so as to avoid the fate of becoming a "shadow economy"
under rampant tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
It is Ukraine's strategic choice to complete the integration
with Europe, Kuchma said, and Ukraine is also for an integration
with countries of the Commonwealth of Independent States on an
equal and mutually beneficial basis.
</P>
<P>
He said Ukraine will pursue close contact with Russia despite
the fact that Boris Yeltsin has postponed his trip to Kiev time
and again.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma also stressed cooperation in the sectors of
trade, science and technology and culture with countries in
northern Africa, western Europe, Latin America, the Middle East,
Asia and the Pacific. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
