<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaanxi Fights Land Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi Province
will carry out a green plan to reverse the trend of serious land
erosion, the provincial governor Cheng Andong was quoted by
today's "China Daily" as saying.
</P>
<P>
The world's worst case of erosion can be seen along the upper
and middle reaches of the Yellow River in the province. In fact,
67 percent of the province's total land mass faces soil erosion,
and the serious problems that accompany it.
</P>
<P>
The continued serious soil erosion has worsened the ecological
environment. Every year, two million hectares of farmland in the
province suffer from drought, waterlogging and sandy wind, which
seriously hinder agricultural development and economic growth, the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
The province is aiming for total vegetation cover by the year
2000. Between 1995 and 1998, during the first stage of the green
plan, the province will plant trees on barren mountains with
suitable conditions.
</P>
<P>
If the drive to make green the loess plateau and the
Qinling-Daba mountains is also successful, the entire province
will see grass and trees cover by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Cheng said he hopes by the year 2000, the province will have
controlled 467,000 ha of desert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
