<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Starts Demolishing Nuclear Test Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan today sealed off the
first of its 186 underground tunnels by directional blasting at
its Semipalatinsk nuclear test site.
</P>
<P>
The blast of the tunnel under Mount Degelen was witnessed by
Kazakh and U.S. nuclear experts, according to the Kazakhstan
Telegraph Agency.
</P>
<P>
As many as 220 nuclear bombs have undergone testing in the
tunnel, with the last one in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan and the United States signed a cooperation accord
last October to demolish the Semipalatinsk nuclear test facility.
The Americans have promised to provide 130 million U.S. dollars to
be used in the destruction of the underground tunnels.
</P>
<P>
Sixty tunnels are planned to be destroyed this year.
</P>
<P>
Semipalatinsk was a major nuclear testing ground for
the former Soviet Union, with 459 tests carried out between
August 29, 1949, and August 1991.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan is one of the four nuclear-armed former Soviet
republics. The others are Russia, Belarus and Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perry: U.S. to Sell Egypt F-16 Fighter Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Perry said today that the United States will sell 21 F-16 jet
fighters and a naval frigate to Egypt to strengthen its role in
safeguarding peace and security in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon chief, who is making a six-day visit to the Balkan
nations and Egypt, made the disclosure to reporters en route from
Tirana to Cairo, reports received here said.
</P>
<P>
Perry told the reporters that he would discuss the sale with
his Egyptian counterpart Mohamed Hussein Tantawi on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Air Force has 160 F-16 jet fighters, but is
anxious to buy more frontline jets to replace aging former
Soviet-made MIG fighters.
</P>
<P>
Perry also disclosed that the Pentagon is preparing to sell
Egypt a third missile frigate. The U.S. Congress has approved the
Pentagon to sell two frigates to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Republican-controlled U.S. Congress had been
notified of the sales and Egypt might pay the F-16s and the
frigate with part of the 1.3 billion-U.S. dollar military aid it
will get from the United States in the fiscal year 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960403.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Albania to Enhance Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Perry said here today that the U.S. administration will promote
its military cooperation with Albania by continuing to provide the
country with military assistance.
</P>
<P>
Perry, who arrived here last Sunday to attend the meeting of
defense ministers of southern Balkan countries, made the remarks
at a press conference after meeting his Albanian counterpart Safet
Zhulali.
</P>
<P>
Under a joint communique issued after the meeting, the two
countries agreed that "peaceful partnership relations" are a
special way to promote the cooperation of the two states in the
defense field.
</P>
<P>
The United States will set up a security and assistance office
in Albania and its military advisors will continue working in the
Albanian Defense Ministry, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that the U.S. will provide an aid including a
supply of military logistic equipment worth 31 million
U.S. dollars and the establishment of a military training center
for Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
