<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ice Melting in Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The ice that created havoc on the
middle and upper reaches of the Yellow River during China's Spring
Festival in February, has finally been freed in the last
obstructed section of the river in north China's Inner Mongolia
Region, according to the local ice-control headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The icy water has passed through Togtoh County in the region,
the headquarters said, and the work to remove the ice has finished.
</P>
<P>
Ice has been melting in the upper reaches of the river, but is
still blocking the lower reaches, pushing the water level up in
the upper reaches, breaking embankments in several places and
causing flooding in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Ice frequently blocks the 860-kilometer-long section of the
river in the region, experts from the headquarters noted.
</P>
<P>
They said that, compared with previous years, temperatures in
the early days of melting period were quite low and then rose
suddenly, accelerating the ice melting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
