<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retired US Generals Call for Ban on Land Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A group of retired high-ranking
American military officers today called on the U.S. government and
the Pentagon to impose a total and earlier ban on land mines.
</P>
<P>
In a "Open Letter to President Clinton," retired U.S. General
Norman Schwarzkopf, the U.S. commander in the Gulf War in 1991,
and 13 other retired generals asked Clinton to "take the lead in
efforts to achieve a total and permanent international ban on the
production, stockpiling, sale and use of anti-personnel land
mines."
</P>
<P>
Land mines are similar to long-banned poison gas in that "they
are hard to control and often have unwanted harmful
consequences... even for those who deploy them," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
"Their indiscriminate effects persist long after hostilities
have ceased, continuing to cause casualties among innocent
people, especially farmers and children," they said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has signed a law imposing a
one-year U.S. moratorium on use of land mines and has supported
an eventual worldwide ban.
</P>
<P>
But some U.S. military officers still argue that land mines
are needed to protect troops and some borders.
</P>
<P>
The letter estimated that 26,000 annual deaths or maimings from
mines around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
