<HEADLINE> Clinton: US Not to Be Involved in Russian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said here today that his administration would not try to get
involved in the upcoming presidential elections in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with Italian President
Oscar Luigi Scalfaro at the White House, Clinton said that the
U.S. government should not "take any position on the elections in
another country" such as Russia.
</P>
<P>
"We have to say clearly that we are on the side of political
reform, democracy, respecting the rights of other countries and
economic reform," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was commenting on the recent press reports that he and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin reached during their meeting at
last month's anti-terrorism summit in Cairo an understanding to
support each other in the presidential elections in Russia and in
the United States later this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president praised Italy for its support for the Bosnia
and Middle East peace processes.
</P>
<P>
"Italy and the United States stand together in the fight
against the forces of hatred and violence," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
