<HEADLINE> Reports Conflict About Crash Site of Plane With  Brown Aboard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The plane carrying U.S. Secretary
of Commerce Ron Brown and a dozen of U.S. business leaders today
hit the top of a hill on the southeastern coast of Croatia,
presumably killing all those on board.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed on CNN, Croatian President Franjo Tudjman said that
the plane, a U.S. military-version of Boeing 737, crashed into the
hill some 16 kilometers from the scenic city of Dubrovnik after
three landing attempts failed.
</P>
<P>
The plane carried 27 people including 12 executives from
various American companies on route from Tuzla to Dubrovnik, where
Brown was expected to start a two-day visit to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Transportation Ministry said in a statement that
the tail of the plane and four bodies have been recovered by a
Croatian search and rescue team near the village of Velji Do,
about 40 kilometers southeast of Dubrovnik.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Defense Department was quoted by CNN as saying that
wreckage of the plane was found in the waters off Dubrovnik, to
further confuse the site of the plane crash.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the crash was still unknown, but bad whether in the
region seemed to be the main factor.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of Brown's visit was to find opportunities for U.S.
companies in the post-war reconstruction of the former Yugoslav
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
