<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-03 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Import 350,000 Tons of Sugar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish cabinet decree approving
the imports of 350,000 tons of beet and cane sugar came into
effect today after a previous import decree expired Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new decree, which will be valid until September 3, was
published today in the Official Gazette.
</P>
<P>
The decree canceled a 200-U.S. dollar per ton customs levy on
imported sugar. However, the customs duty on sugar imports will
rise to 47 percent from a previous three percent, the Gazette said.
</P>
<P>
The duty on sugar imports will rise to 100 percent starting on
September 3 in line with Turkey's import regime which ties it to
the Customs pact with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
An official from Turkey's Foreign Trade Undersecretariat said
that the newly imposed 47 percent customs duty, almost an
equivalent to the 200-dollar customs levy, means the abolishment
of the double taxation in the customs in line with the new import
regime.
</P>
<P>
The previous decree, which was put into effect on December 30,
1995, allowed import of 300,000 tons of sugar by April 1 and cut
the customs levy on imported sugar to 200-dollar per ton from
400-dollar per ton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
